# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mexico
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mexico/14th-parallel-north] The **11th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 11 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:mexico/14th-parallel-north] It crosses Africa, the Indian Ocean, South Asia, Southeast Asia, the Pacific Ocean, Central America, South America, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:mexico/14th-parallel-north] At this latitude the sun is visible for 12 hours, 46 minutes during the summer solstice and 11 hours, 29 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:mexico/14th-parallel-north] In Thailand, a 1966 cabinet resolution restricts the rights of non-Thai companies to conduct mineral exploration or mining operations north of this parallel.
[src:mexico/14th-parallel-north] The border between Ghana and what was then French Upper Volta (now Burkina Faso) was fixed by treaty between the French and British at the Conference of Paris in 1898, to be the 11th parallel.
[src:mexico/14th-parallel-north] The border does not follow the boundary exactly, but follows it approximately, crossing over it several times.
[src:mexico/14th-parallel-north] The **12th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 12 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:mexico/14th-parallel-north] At this latitude the sun is visible for 12 hours, 50 minutes during the summer solstice and 11 hours, 25 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:mexico/14th-parallel-north] The **13th parallel north** is a circle of latitude 13 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:mexico/14th-parallel-north] It crosses Africa, Asia, the Indian Ocean, the Pacific Ocean, Central America, the Caribbean, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:mexico/14th-parallel-north] At this latitude, the sun is visible for 12 hours 53 minutes during the summer solstice and 11 hours 22 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:mexico/14th-parallel-north] The **14th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 14 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:mexico/14th-parallel-north] At this latitude the sun is visible for 12 hours, 57 minutes during the summer solstice and 11 hours, 18 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:mexico/14th-parallel-north] The **15th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 15 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:mexico/14th-parallel-north] It crosses the Saharan fringe (the Sahel) in Africa, three key peninsulas of Asia (between which parts of the Indian Ocean), the Pacific Ocean, an isthmus of Central America, the southern Caribbean, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:mexico/14th-parallel-north] In the Chadian-Libyan conflict of 1978 to 1987, its intra-Chad part came to be known as the "Red Line", separating opposing combatants, above all in Operation Manta.
[src:mexico/14th-parallel-north] At this latitude the sun is visible for 13 hours, 1 minute during the summer solstice and 11 hours, 14 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The **Federal Constitution of the United Mexican States of 1824** (Spanish: *Constitución Federal de los Estados Unidos Mexicanos de 1824*) was the first constitution of Mexico, enacted on October 4 of 1824, inaugurating the First Mexican Republic.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] During the Mexican War of Independence, the liberal dominated Spanish Cortes of Cádiz had included representatives from the colonies, and taken into account many of the colonial grievances which were leading to independence.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The consequent liberal Constitution of 1812, was promulgated during the insurgency led by José María Morelos.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] It established a system of 'provincial deputations' which granted more autonomy to local governments in the colonies while also providing for freedom of speech.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Mexico finally gained its independence under the Plan of Iguala promulgated by Agustín de Iturbide, which planned for Mexico to be ruled by a member of the Spanish Bourbons, in either a personal union or with a member of the royal family travelling to Mexico to establish a new throne.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The Spanish government refused the offer and a popular demonstration led to Iturbide himself assuming the throne.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The ill-fated Empire which lasted less than a year, never managed to produce a constitution, and the failure to do so was one of the accusations Iturbide levelled at congress when he controversially dissolved it.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The lack of clearly defined powers for congress and the emperor also contributed to the clashes which ultimately produced a successful rebellion against Emperor Iturbide in early 1823.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The Empire was abolished and congress established the Supreme Executive Power to serve as a provisional government.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] On the May 21, 1823, elections were announced for a new congress whose term was scheduled to begin on October 31.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Rules for the new election were published on June 17.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The new congress elected in late October was mainly federalist in composition.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] It first met on November 7, 1823, and soon divided itself into two main factions: the federalists, whose most prominent voice was Miguel Ramos Arizpe, and the centralists, whose most prominent voice was Servando Teresa de Mier.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Through the minister of justice, the executive announced to the congress on November 14, that they must now set to work on answering the popular call to establish the government most suited for the nation.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] A committee consisting of Miguel Ramos Arizpe, Juan de Dios Cañedo, Miguel Argüelles, Rafael Mangino, Tomás Vargas, José de Jesús Huerta, and Manuel Crescencio Rejón, submitted an *Acta Constitutiva* (draft of a constitution) on 20 November.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The group completed the draft of the charter in a few days.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] This was possible because the document was based on the shared Hispanic political theory and practice that Mexicans, the former novohispanos, knew well, since they had played a significant role in shaping it.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] In the years since Napoleon had invaded Spain in 1808, the political entities that formed the Mexican nation in 1821 had undergone a series of rapid political changes that politicized the majority of the population and led to a vibrant political discourse.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The Directioners Constitution of 1812 and its institutions of government were well known; seven proposals for a Mexican constitution had been debated throughout the country in the previous months.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The constituent congress, therefore, was filled with educated men with diverse ideas and extensive political experience at the local, state, national, and international levels.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] A few, like Ramos Arizpe and Guridi y Alcocer, had served in the Cortes in Spain and had participated in the discussions of the Constitution of 1812.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] In addition, Ramos Arizpe had been working on a federal constitution for some time.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Lorenzo de Zavala was president of the congress that approved the constitution.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The Acta Constitutiva submitted by the committee was modelled on the Hispanic Constitution of 1812.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Most of its articles were based on the Peninsular document; a few were adopted verbatim from that charter.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] For example, on the question of sovereignty the Hispanic Constitution stated: "Sovereignty resides essentially in the nation and, therefore, it [the nation] possesses the exclusive right to adopt the form of government that seems most convenient for its conservation and prosperity".
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Although the deputies relied on their first constitutional experience, the Constitution of 1812, they did not slavishly copy the Hispanic model.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] His principal critics were radical federalists like Juan de Dios Cañedo, deputy from Jalisco, who challenged the need for an article declaring national sovereignty.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] He asked: that the article be deleted because in a republican federal government each state is sovereign.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] (...) Therefore, it is impossible to conceive how sovereignty, which is the origin and source of authority and power, can be divided among the many states. [T]hat is why the first constitution of the United States [the Articles of Confederation] (...) does not mention national sovereignty.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] And, therefore, (...) Article 1 which discusses the nation should not be approved because it is not appropriate in the system we now have.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The Acta, unlike the Hispanic constitution, did not grant exclusive or even preponderant sovereignty to the nation, because the states also claimed sovereignty.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Accordingly, Article 6 stated: "Its integral parts are independent, free, and sovereign States in that which exclusively concerns their administration and interior government".
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The issue of sovereignty remained at heart a question of the division of power between the national and the state governments.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] It was an issue that would be debated at length in the months to come.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The proponents of state sovereignty—the confederalists—were challenged by some less radical federalist delegates who argued that only the nation could be sovereign.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Because these men stressed the need to endow the national government with sufficient power to sustain national interests, they are often mistakenly considered centralists.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Servando Teresa de Mier, their outstanding spokesman, argued that people wrongly considered him a centralist, an error that arose from an unnecessarily restrictive definition of federalism.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] He indicated that federalism existed in many forms: the Netherlands, Germany, Switzerland and the United States were federations, yet each was different.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Mier advocated the establishment of a unique brand of federalism suited to Mexico.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] He believed that local realities precluded the adoption of the extreme form of federalism—confederalism—championed by states' righters.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] He declared: "I have always been in favour of a federation, but a reasonable and moderate federation.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] For these reasons, Mier voted in favour of Article 5, which established a federal republic, while opposing Article 6, which granted sovereignty to the states.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Neither the advocates of states' rights, like Cañedo, nor the proponents of national sovereignty, like Mier, triumphed.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Instead, a compromise emerged: shared sovereignty, as advocated by moderate federalists such as Ramos Arizpe.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Throughout the debates, he and others argued that although the nation was sovereign, the states should control their internal affairs.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The group saw no conflict between Article 3, which declared that sovereignty resided in the nation, and Article 6, which granted sovereignty to the states on internal matters.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The moderates were able to forge shifting coalitions to pass both articles.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] First, they brought Article 3 to a vote.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] A coalition of the proponents of national sovereignty, the advocates of shared sovereignty, and a few centralists passed the article by a wide margin.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] To secure passage of Article 6, those favouring approval succeeded in having the question brought to the floor in two parts.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The first vote, on the section of Article 6 which indicated that the states were independent and free to manage their own affairs, passed by a wide margin, since the wording pleased all the confederalist/federalist groups, including the one led by Father Mier.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Only seven centralist deputies opposed the measure.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Then Congress examined the section of Article 6 which declared that the states were sovereign.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The coalition divided on this issue: Father Mier and his supporters joined the centralists in voting against the measure.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Nevertheless, the proponents of states' rights and those who believed in shared sovereignty possessed enough strength to pass the measure by a margin of 41 to 28 votes.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The states did not just share sovereignty with the national government; they obtained the financial means to enforce their authority.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] They gained considerable taxing power at the expense of the federal government, which lost approximately half the revenue formerly collected by the viceregal administration.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] To compensate for that loss, the states were to pay the national government a contingente assessed for each state according to its means.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] As a result, the nation would have to depend upon the goodwill of the states to finance or fulfil its responsibilities.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The constituent congress's decision to share sovereignty, moreover, did not settle the question of the division of power within the national government.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Although all agreed on the traditional concept of separation of powers among the legislative, executive, and judicial branches, most congressmen believed that the legislature should be dominant.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Recent Hispanic and Mexican experience had fostered a distrust of executive power.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Therefore, the earlier Mexican Cortes had established a plural executive, the Supreme Executive Power.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Since that body was perceived as subservient to the legislature, neither the provinces nor the Second Constituent Congress bothered to appoint a new executive.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The authors of the Acta Constitutiva, however, proposed in Article 16 that executive power be conferred "on an individual with the title of president of the Mexican Federation, who must be a citizen by birth of said federation and have attained at least thirty-five years of age".
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The proposal led to a heated debate that transcended the former division between states' righters and strong nationalist coalitions.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] While Cañedo supported Ramos Arizpe in favouring a single executive, others, including Rejón and Guridi y Alcocer, insisted on the need to weaken executive power by establishing a plural executive.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Ramos Arizpe proposed that the president govern with the aid of a council of government.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] But that was not sufficient to mollify the opposition, which had the majority in congress.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The opponents of a single executive presented several counter-proposals.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Demetrio Castillo of Oaxaca suggested that a president, a vice-president and an alternate, called designee, should govern.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Each would have a vote, but the president would cast the deciding one.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Rejón, instead, recommended that three individuals form the Supreme Executive Power; their terms would be staggered so that one member would always possess seniority, but no individual would serve more than three years.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Guridi y Alcocer proposed that the executive power be conferred on two persons.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] He argued that the best solution was to merge the experiences of ancient Rome, Spain, and the United States.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Therefore, he urged that the two members of the executive power be backed by two alternates, who might resolve any differences that arose between the two members of the executive.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Article 16 of the Acta Constitutiva was put to a vote on 2 January 1824 at an extraordinary session.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] As a result, the congress did not address Article 17, which dealt with the vice-president.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The proposal to establish a president and a vice-president was one of the few instances in which the second constitution of the United States served as a model.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The majority did not agree with the proposal because it feared the possibility of one individual dominating Congress through military or popular forces, as Iturbide had done.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The commission on the constitution revised the articles on the executive a number of times, but could not obtain support for its proposals.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The fear of provincial disorder also influenced the debate.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] After Articles 5 and 6 of the Acta Constitutiva had been approved, several provinces decided to implement their right to form their own government.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The national administration viewed their actions with concern, particularly because some movements were also anti-European Spaniards.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The revolt of 12 December in Querétaro, for example, demanded the expulsion of gachupines (Spaniards who had come to Mexico) from the country.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] A similar uprising occurred later in Cuernavaca.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] In both instances, the national government sent forces to restore order.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Then, on 23 December, Puebla declared itself a sovereign, free, and independent state.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The authorities in Mexico City immediately concluded that the military commander of the province, General José Antonio de Echávarri, was responsible for the "revolt".
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Therefore, the government dispatched an army under the command of Generals Manuel Gómez Pedraza and Vicente Guerrero to restore order.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The forces of the national government approached the capital city of Puebla at the end of December 1823.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] After lengthy negotiations, General Gómez Pedraza proposed that, since Congress was about to issue the convocatoria for national and state elections, the leaders of Puebla renounce their earlier action and hold new elections.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The convocatoria was received in Puebla on 12 January 1824.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Elections were held throughout the province and a new state government was inaugurated on 22 March 1824.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Although the national government had maintained order in the nation, the revolt led by General Jose María Lobato on 20 January 1824 demonstrated that the plural executive could not act with the unity of purpose and the speed necessary to quell a large scale uprising in the capital.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The rebels demanded the dismissal of Spaniards from government jobs and their expulsion from the country.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Lobato managed to win support of the garrisons in the capital and the government seemed on the verge of capitulation when the Supreme Executive Power convinced Congress to declare Lobato an outlaw and to grant the executive sufficient power to quell the rebellion.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] As a result of the crisis, the majority in Congress eventually decided to establish an executive branch composed of a president and a vice-president.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The creation of a single executive, however, did not mean that Congress had accepted a strong presidency.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Most Mexicans continued to favour legislative supremacy.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The Mexican charter, like the Hispanic constitution, severely restricted the power of the chief executive.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The Constitution of 1824 created a quasi-parliamentary system in which the ministers of state answered to the congress.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Consequently, the minister of interior and foreign relations acted as a quasi-prime minister.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The creation of a national government did not end the tensions between the provinces and Mexico City.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The debate over the location of the country's capital sparked a new conflict.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The national elite favoured making the "Imperial City of Mexico" the capital of the republic.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] During 1823, while discussing the importance of local control, they also emphasised the need to maintain a "centre of unity", that is, a capital.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] However, a significant number pointedly refused to bestow that honour upon Mexico City.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The special committee on the nation's capital recommended to the Constituent Congress on 31 May 1824 that another city, Querétaro, become the capital, and that the territory around it become the federal district.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] After a heated debate, Congress rejected the proposal to move the capital from Mexico City.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Thereafter, the discussion centred on whether or not a federal district should be created.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The ayuntamiento and the provincial deputation of Mexico were vehemently against such action.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Indeed, the provincial legislature threatened secession and civil war if Mexico City were federalised.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Nevertheless, on 30 October Congress voted fifty-two to thirty-one to make Mexico City the nation's capital and to create a federal district.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] After months of debate, Congress ratified the constitution, on 4 October 1824.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Article 3: The religion of the Mexican nation is and will permanently be the Roman, Catholic, Apostolic [religion].
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The nation protects her with wise and just laws and prohibits the exercise of any other [religion].
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The Mexican nation adopts for its government a representative, popular, federal republic.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] A constitutional law will determine the status of Tlaxcala.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The supreme executive power of the federation is deposited in only one individual who shall be called President of the United Mexican States (Estados Unidos Mexicanos).
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] There will also be a vice president who, in case of the physical or moral incapacity of the president, will receive all his authority and prerogatives.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Like the *Acta Constitutiva*, the Constitution of 1824 was modelled on the Hispanic Constitution of 1812, not, as is often asserted, on the US Constitution of 1787.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Although superficially similar to the latter although it adopted a few practical applications from the U.S.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Constitution, such as the executive, the Mexican document was based primarily on Hispanic constitutional and legal precedents.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] For example, although the Constitution of 1824 created a president, in Mexico the office was subordinate to the legislature.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Since Mexico was essentially confederalist, rather than federalist, the Mexican Charter was closer in spirit to the first U.S.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Constitution, the Articles of Confederation, than to the U.S.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Entire sections of the Cádiz Charter were repeated verbatim in the Mexican document because Mexicans did not reject their Hispanic heritage, and because men who drafted the new republican constitution had served in the Cortes of Cádiz and had helped write the 1812 Constitution.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Both the 1812 Constitution and the Mexican Constitution of 1824 established powerful legislatures and weak executives.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] However, the 1824 constitution was not a mere copy of that of 1812.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Events in Mexico, particularly the assertion of states' rights by the former provinces, forced Congress to frame a constitution to meet the unique circumstances of the nation.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The principal innovations (republicanism, federalism, and the presidency) were adopted to address Mexico's new reality.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The monarchy was abolished because both Fernando VII and Agustín I had failed as rulers, not because Mexicans imitated the U.S.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Federalism arose naturally from Mexico's earlier political experience.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The provincial deputations created by the Constitution of Cádiz simply converted themselves into states.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Unlike the 1812 document, the Mexican charter gave the states significant taxing power.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Although modeled on the Spanish Constitution of 1812, the new charter did not address a number of issues included in the earlier document because the new Mexican federation shared sovereignty between the national government and the states.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Thus, unlike the Constitution of Cádiz, which defined citizenship, the Mexican Constitution of 1824 remained silent on the subject.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Similarly, it did not define who possessed the suffrage or the size of the population required to establish *ayuntamientos* (town councils), two significant factors in determining the popular nature of the Hispanic constitutional system.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Those decisions were the prerogatives of the states.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The constitutions of the states of the Mexican federation varied, but they generally followed the precedents of the Constitution of Cádiz.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Most state constitutions explicitly defined the people in their territory as being citizens of the state; they were chiapanecos, sonorenses, chihuahuenses, duranguenses, guanajuatenses, etc.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Some states, such as Mexico and Puebla, simply referred to "the natives [sic] and citizens of the estate." The constitution is silent on the explicit status of Mexican women.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Following the Cádiz model, all states established indirect elections.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] A few, however, introduced property qualifications.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Many also followed the constitution of 1812 in allowing *ayuntamientos* in towns with more than 1,000 persons, but some raised the population requirements to 2,000, 3,000 or 4,000.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Tabasco permitted only the *cabeceras* (head towns) of the *partido* (district) to have *ayuntamientos*.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] It introduced the system of federalism in a popular representative republic with Catholicism as official religion.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The 1824 constitution does not expressly state the rights of citizens.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The right to equality of citizens was restricted by the continuation of military and ecclesiastical courts.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The Mexican nation adopts as its form of government a popular federal representative republic.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Political freedom of press in the federation and the states (paragraph 1).
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] It provides the figure of vice president, who in case of physical or moral impossibility of the president, exercise the powers and prerogatives of the latter.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The term of the president and vice president shall be four years.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] , the Circuit Courts and the District Courts.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] consists of eleven members divided into three rooms and a prosecutor.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The individual state governments will be formed by the same three powers.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Although this was not stipulated in the constitution, slavery was prohibited in the Republic.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Miguel Hidalgo promulgated the abolition in Guadalajara on 6 December 1810.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] President Guadalupe Victoria declared slavery abolished too, but it was President Vicente Guerrero who made the decree of *Abolition of Slavery* on 15 September 1829.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] At the time of the promulgation of the Constitution, the nation was composed of 19 free states and 3 territories.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] That same year, two changes were made in the structure, resulting finally in 19 free states, 5 territories and the federal district.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The central states—Mexico, Puebla, Querétaro, Guanajuato, Veracruz and Michoacán—which were the most populated, worked as an administrative decentralization.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The states of the periphery—Zacatecas, Coahuila y Texas, Durango, Chihuahua, Jalisco, San Luis Potosí and Nuevo León—acquired a moderate confederalism.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The states furthest from the center—Yucatán, Sonora y Sinaloa, Tamaulipas and Las Californias—acquired a radical confederalism.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Without the existence of established political parties, three political tendencies are distinguished.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The first still supported the empire of Iturbide, but was a minority.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The second was influenced by the Yorkist Lodge of freemasonry, whose philosophy was radical Federalism and also encouraged an anti-Spanish sentiment largely promoted by the American plenipotentiary Joel Roberts Poinsett.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] And the third was influenced by the Scottish Lodge of freemasonry, which had been introduced to Mexico by the Spaniards themselves, favored Centralism, and yearned for the recognition of the new nation by Spain and the Holy See.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] With the consummation of independence, the "Royal Patronage" was gone, the federal government and state governments now considered these rights to belong to the State.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The way to manage church property was the point that most polarized the opinions of the political class.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Members of the Yorkist Lodge intended to use church property to clean up the finances, the members of the Scottish Lodge considered the alternative anathema.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] According to the federal commitment, states should provide an amount of money and men for the army, or *blood quota*.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The federal budget was insufficient to pay debt, defense, and surveillance of borders, and states resisted meeting the *blood quota*, sometimes meeting that debt with criminals.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Some state constitutions were more radical and took supplies to practice *patronage* locally, under the banner of "freedom and progress".
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] In 1835, there was a drastic shift to the new Mexican Nation.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] On 30 December 1836, interim president José Justo Corro issued the Seven Constitutional Laws, which replaced the Constitution.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] Secondary laws were approved on 24 May 1837.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The Seven Constitutional Laws, among other things, replaced the "free states" with French-style "departments", centralizing national power in Mexico City.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] This created an era of political instability, unleashing conflicts between the central government and the former states.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The Texas annexation and the border conflict after the annexation led to the Mexican–American War.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] As a result, the Constitution of 1824 was restored by interim President José Mariano Salas on 22 August 1846.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] In 1847, *The Reform Act* was published, which officially incorporated, with some changes, the Federal Constitution of 1824, to operate while the next constitution was drafted.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] This federalist phase culminated in 1853.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] The Plan of Ayutla, which had a federalist orientation, was proclaimed on 1 March 1854.
[src:mexico/1824-constitution-of-mexico] In 1855, Juan Álvarez, interim President of the Republic, issued the call for the Constituent Congress, which began its work on 17 February 1856 to produce the Federal Constitution of the United Mexican States of 1857.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] These were the first Olympic Games to be staged in Latin America, the first to be staged in a Spanish-speaking country, and the first to be staged in the Global South.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] Consequently, these games also marked the first time that there would be a gap of two Olympic Games not to be held in Europe.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] They were also the first Games to use an all-weather (smooth) track for track and field events instead of the traditional cinder track, as well as the first example of the Olympics exclusively using electronic timekeeping equipment.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] The 1968 Games were the third to be held in the last quarter of the year, after the 1956 Games in Melbourne and the 1964 Games in Tokyo.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] The 1968 Mexican Student Movement was crushed days prior, hence the Games were correlated to the government's repression.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold and overall medals for the last time until the 1984 Summer Games.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] On 18 October 1963, at the 60th IOC Session in Baden-Baden, West Germany, Mexico City finished ahead of bids from Detroit, Buenos Aires and Lyon to host the Games.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] The 1968 torch relay recreated the route taken by Christopher Columbus to the New World, journeying from Greece through Italy and Spain to San Salvador Island, Bahamas, and then on to Mexico.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] American sculptor James Metcalf, an expatriate in Mexico, won the commission to forge the Olympic torch for the 1968 Summer Games.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] The logo is viewed as a Mexican cultural icon.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] Inspired by the Olympic rings symbol, the five circles are incorporated into the year number 68 and unified with the word Mexico.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] The radiating parallel lines were extended to fit the poster format.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] This graphic design was printed in various vibrant colors.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] It was the subject of dispute between American designer Lance Wyman and Mexican architect Pedro Ramírez Vázquez over who originated the graphic concepts.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] Architect Eduardo Terrazas also worked under Ramirez's direction to develop the concept.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] A pink chacmool jaguar, which was sold in souvenir shops, is considered an unofficial mascot.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] The dove of peace was also a symbol of the Games, which was appropriated by student protesters with a bayonet piercing it.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] The nominal obstacle behind South Africa's exclusion thus removed, the country was thus provisionally invited to the Games, on the understanding that all segregation and discrimination in sport would be eliminated by the 1972 Games.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] However, African countries and African American athletes promised to boycott the Games if South Africa was present, and Eastern Bloc countries threatened to do likewise.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] In April 1968 the IOC conceded that "it would be most unwise for South Africa to participate".
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] It was thus the first Olympics where South Africa was positively excluded, which continued until the Olympics of 1992.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] Responding to growing social unrest and protests, the government of Mexico had increased economic and political suppression, against labor unions in particular, in the decade building up to the Olympics.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] A series of protest marches in the city in August gathered significant attendance, with an estimated 500,000 taking part on 27 August.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] President Gustavo Díaz Ordaz ordered the police occupation of the National Autonomous University of Mexico in September, but protests continued.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] Ten days before the start of the Olympics, the government ordered the gathering in Plaza de las Tres Culturas to be broken up.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] Some 5000 soldiers and 200 tankettes surrounded the plaza.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] Hundreds of protesters and civilians were killed and over 1000 were arrested.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] At the time, the event was portrayed in the national media as the military suppression of a violent student uprising, but later analysis indicates that the gathering was peaceful prior to the army's advance.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] Both were members of the Olympic Project for Human Rights.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] International Olympic Committee (IOC) president Avery Brundage deemed it to be a domestic political statement unfit for the apolitical, international forum the Olympic Games were intended to be.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] In response to their actions, he ordered Smith and Carlos suspended from the US team and banned from the Olympic Village.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] When the US Olympic Committee refused, Brundage threatened to ban the entire US track team.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] This threat led to the expulsion of the two athletes from the Games.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] Peter Norman, the Australian sprinter who came second in the 200-meter race, also wore an Olympic Project for Human Rights badge during the medal ceremony.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] Norman was the one who suggested that Carlos and Smith wear one glove each.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] His actions resulted in him being ostracized by Australian media and a reprimand by his country's Olympic authorities.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] He was not sent to the 1972 games, despite several times making the qualifying time, though opinions differ over whether that was due to the 1968 protest.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] When Australia hosted the 2000 Summer Olympics, he had no part in the opening ceremony, though the significance of that is also debated.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] In 2006, after Norman died of a heart attack, Smith and Carlos were pallbearers at Norman's funeral.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] The action was Čáslavská's silent protest against the recent Soviet invasion of Czechoslovakia.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] Her protest was repeated when she accepted her medal for her floor exercise routine when the judges changed the preliminary scores of the Soviet Larisa Petrik to allow her to tie with Čáslavská for the gold.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] The organizers declined to hold a judo tournament at the Olympics, even though it had been a full-medal sport four years earlier.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] This was the last time judo was not included in the Olympic games.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] Baseball had been featured as a demonstration sport at the 1964 Tokyo Games, but not in 1968, despite Mexico's baseball heritage.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] Instead, a separate international tournament was held in Mexico City, shortly after the conclusion of the Olympic Games.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] East Germany and West Germany competed as separate entities for the first time at a Summer Olympiad, and would remain so through 1988.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] Barbados competed for the first time as an independent country.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] Also competing for the first time in a Summer Olympiad were British Honduras (now Belize), Central African Republic, the Democratic Republic of the Congo (as Congo-Kinshasa), El Salvador, Guinea, Honduras, Kuwait, Nicaragua, Paraguay, Sierra Leone, and the United States Virgin Islands.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] Singapore returned to the Games as an independent country after competing as part of the Malaysian team in 1964.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] Suriname and Libya actually competed for the first time (in 1960 and 1964, respectively, they took part in the Opening Ceremony, but their athletes later withdrew from the competition).
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] The People's Republic of China last competed at the 1952 Summer Games but had since withdrawn from the IOC due to a dispute with the Republic of China over the right to represent China.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] North Korea withdrew from the 1968 Games because of two incidents that strained its relations with the IOC.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] First, the IOC had barred North Korean track and field athletes from the 1968 Games because they had participated in the rival Games of the New Emerging Forces (GANEFO) in 1966.
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] Secondly, the IOC had ordered the nation to compete under the name "North Korea" in the 1968 Games, whereas the country itself would have preferred its official name: "Democratic People's Republic of Korea".
[src:mexico/1968-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1968 Games.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The **1970 FIFA World Cup** was the ninth edition of the FIFA World Cup, the quadrennial international football championship for men's senior national teams.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Held from 31 May to 21 June in Mexico, it was the first World Cup tournament held outside Europe and South America, and also the first hosted in North America.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Teams representing 75 nations from all six populated continents entered the competition, and its qualification rounds began in May 1968.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Fourteen teams qualified from this process to join host nation Mexico and defending champions England in the 16-team final tournament.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] El Salvador, Israel and Morocco made their debut appearances at the final stage.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] In the tournament final, Brazil won 4–1 against Italy, another FIFA two-time champion (and UEFA Euro 1968 winner).
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Brazil also overcame another two-time champion and South American champions Uruguay, by 3–1 in the semi-final, and defending champions England 1–0 in the group stage as they were also eliminated by West Germany in the quarter-finals.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] This is currently the only time that the winning team defeated the European and South American champions alongside the tournament's defending champions.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The win gave Brazil their third World Cup title, which allowed them to permanently keep the Jules Rimet Trophy, and a new trophy was introduced in 1974.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The victorious team, led by Carlos Alberto and featuring players such as Pelé, Gérson, Jairzinho, Rivellino and Tostão, is often cited as the greatest football team of all time.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] They achieved a perfect record of wins in all six games in the finals, as well as winning all their qualifying fixtures.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Despite the issues of altitude and high temperature, the finals largely produced attacking football which created an average goals per game record not since bettered by any subsequent World Cup Finals.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] With the advancements in satellite communications, the 1970 Finals attracted a new record television audience for the FIFA World Cup as games were broadcast live around the world and, in a few cases, in colour—the first time that that was the case.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Mexico was chosen as the host nation on 8 October 1964 vote at the FIFA congress in Tokyo, where the only other bid submitted was by Argentina, which would go on to host the 1978 World Cup.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The 1970 selection of Mexico as host would mark several distinctions.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] It was the first World Cup that was staged in North America and the first to be staged outside of South America and Europe.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Further distinction would come to Mexico at the 1986 World Cup when it became the first country to host the FIFA World Cup twice after stepping in as a substitute for Colombia, which was struggling financially.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] A total of 75 teams entered the 1970 FIFA World Cup, and 73 were required to qualify.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Due to rejected entries and withdrawals, 68 teams eventually participated in the qualifying stages, including eight for the first time.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Mexico as the host nation and England as reigning World Cup champions were granted automatic qualification, with the remaining 14 finals places divided among the continental confederations.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Eight places were available to teams from UEFA (Europe), three for CONMEBOL (South America), one for CAF (Africa), one for a team from either the AFC or the OFC (Asia/Oceania), and one for CONCACAF (North and Central America and Caribbean).
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Thus, while Morocco was the first African team to qualify for the World Cup since Egypt in 1934, they were the first to be assured qualification via their own continental zone, since Egypt had to play against the British-occupied Palestine to qualify for the 1934 tournament.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The draw for the qualifying stages was conducted on 1 February 1968, with matches beginning in May 1968 and the final fixtures being concluded in December 1969.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] North Korea, quarter-finalists at the previous tournament, were disqualified during the process after refusing to play in Israel for political reasons.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] El Salvador qualified for the finals after beating Honduras in a play-off match, which was the catalyst for a four-day conflict in July 1969 known as the Football War.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Half of the eventual qualifying teams had also been present at the previous World Cup, but three teams qualified for the first time: El Salvador, Israel and Morocco, while Peru, Romania, Belgium and Sweden made their first World Cup appearances since 1930, 1938, 1954 and 1958 respectively.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Czechoslovakia returned to the World Cup stage after missing out in 1966.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The following 16 teams qualified for the final tournament.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] As of 2026, this was the only time Israel qualified for a FIFA World Cup finals, and also the only time Argentina failed to qualify (they declined to participate in 1938, 1950 and 1954).
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Five stadiums in five cities were selected to host the World Cup matches.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Alternative venues in Hidalgo state and the port city of Veracruz were also considered.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Each group was based solely in one city with exception of Group 2, which was staged in both Puebla and Toluca.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Aside from the Estadio Luis Dosal, all the stadia had only been constructed during the 1960s, as Mexico prepared to host both the World Cup and the 1968 Summer Olympics.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The stadium construction cost for the four smaller venues were around US$11 million, while the final stadium in Mexico City cost US$20 million.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] All sites were in Central Mexico, on the Mexican Plateau; none were below 1,500 metres (4,900 ft) above sea level.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The altitude of the venues varied and the importance of acclimatisation was strongly considered by all the participating teams.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] As a result, in contrast to the previous tournament staged in England, most teams arrived in the region well in advance of their opening fixtures to prepare for this factor.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Some teams had already experienced the local conditions when competing in the football competition at 1968 Summer Olympics.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] At an elevation in excess of 2,660 metres (8,730 ft) above sea level, Toluca was the highest of the venues; Guadalajara was the lowest at 1,500 m (4,920 ft).
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] In addition to the altitude, all five locations had hot and rainy weather where temperatures would regularly go past 32 °C (90 °F).
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Of the five stadia used for the 32 matches played, the largest and most utilised venue was the Azteca Stadium in Mexico City, which hosted 10 total matches including the final and match for third place, and all of Group 1's matches (which included all of host Mexico's matches).
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The Jalisco Stadium in Guadalajara hosted eight matches including all of Group 3's matches and a semi-final.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The Nou Camp Stadium in Leon hosted seven matches, which consisted of all of Group 4's matches and a quarter-final match.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The Luis Dosal stadium in Toluca hosted four matches, and Cuauhtémoc stadium in Puebla hosted three matches and was the only stadium of the five used for this tournament not to host any knockout rounds.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The 16 qualified teams were divided into four groups of four.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Each group was played as a single round-robin in which each team would play each of the others in their group once.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Teams were ranked by the number of points earned from their matches (two points were awarded for a win and one for a draw), and goal difference was used as the primary tie-breaker; if two teams finished level on both points and goal difference, lots were drawn to separate them.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] This method was used to separate the top two teams in Group 1 (Soviet Union and Mexico), but it was not used to separate Bulgaria and Morocco in Group 4, despite them finishing level on points and goal difference, as they were both eliminated anyways.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The top two teams from each group progressed to the knockout stage.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] In all knockout matches, extra time was played if the teams were drawn after 90 minutes.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] If teams were still tied after extra-time, drawing of lots would have been used in all matches other than the final.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] FIFA did not announce in advance what would happen if the final itself were to be drawn after extra time.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] In the event, all knockout matches were decided in either regular time or extra time.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Instead, the 16 qualified teams were divided into four pots comprising 'geographical groupings' decided by a vote of the FIFA Organising Committee, which for the composition of pot 1, 3 and 4 also took into account the teams' strengths and even political considerations.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The tournament structure ensured that teams grouped within the same pot would not meet each other before the quarter-finals at the earliest.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The system of politically decided pots hereby ensured that Israel and Morocco would not be drawn to face each other after Morocco had earlier threatened to withdraw from the tournament, as they had done from the Olympic football tournament two years earlier, if that were the case.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The draw was staged in Mexico City, Mexico on 10 January 1970 in the Maria Isabel Hotel, which served as FIFA's headquarters during the competition.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The teams were drawn into the four groups, which had their locations defined in advance: Group 1 being staged in Mexico City, Group 2 in Puebla and Toluca, Group 3 in Guadalajara and Group 4 in León.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Ahead of the draw, the FIFA regulations had predetermined that the hosts Mexico would be in Group 1 and so based in the capital city, and that England as holders would be based together with Group 3 in Guadalajara, the tournament's second largest stadium.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Keeping the defending champion (holders) apart from meeting the hosts in the group stage either by seeding or predetermined group positions, was a practiced tradition throughout the history of the FIFA World Cup, with 1934 and 1954 being the only two exceptions.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The 10-year-old daughter of Guillermo Cañedo, president of the Mexican Football Federation and chief of the FIFA Organising Committee, drew out the teams from four silver cups, so that each of the four groups featured one drawn team respectively from pot 1, pot 2, pot 3 and pot 4.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] A tournament squad was limited to no more than 22 players; Morocco named only 19 players in their squad.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Following the opening ceremony host nation Mexico faced the Soviet Union; this was the last time until the 2006 World Cup that the host nation's first match rather than the World Cup holders' began the tournament.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Both this opening match of Group 1 and many others during the competition kicked off at noon for the benefit of European television schedules, meaning play under the midday sun.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The match produced a goalless draw, prompting some media to predict the entire tournament would be played at the slow tempo that featured in this game given the conditions involved.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Following the half-time interval Anatoliy Puzach became the first substitute to be used in FIFA World Cup history as the Soviets made use of the new competition rule.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Both teams won their remaining two games to progress from the group at the expense of Belgium and World Cup debutants El Salvador.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Group 2 was the lowest-scoring of the groups with only six goals in its six matches as Uruguay, reigning South America champions, and Italy, the reigning European champions, edged past Sweden and Israel.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Sweden would have progressed if they had produced a two-goal victory against Uruguay in their final game, but it was not until the final minute that they scored the only goal of the game.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Hours before the game FIFA elected to replace the scheduled referee after bribery rumours – later dismissed by FIFA – arose in Mexico.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The 1–0 result meant that Uruguay advanced, to be joined by Italy after they avoided defeat in the group finale against Israel.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Owing to the lack of a seeding system, Group 3 allowed the reigning World Cup holders England to be paired together with the two-time former champion Brazil, considered by many the pre-tournament favourites for the trophy.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] England's preparations were hampered by the arrest of their captain Bobby Moore in Colombia for allegedly stealing a bracelet from a jeweller's shop; the charges were later dropped.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The attitude of their manager Alf Ramsey and the English media in general was perceived by many locals as unfriendly and xenophobic toward Mexico's hosting of the competition, which meant the English team received a largely hostile response during the competition.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] With both having won their opening games – against Czechoslovakia and Romania, respectively – Brazil met England in the group's most famed match.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Although Gordon Banks in the English goal denied Pelé from close range with a reflex save that Pelé himself cited as the greatest of his career, a second-half goal from Jairzinho won the match for Brazil, after which England squandered several excellent opportunities to equalise.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Both teams then won their final group games to progress to the knockout stage.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Play in Group 4 began with Bulgaria taking a two-goal lead against Peru, but a second half comeback gave the South Americans a 3–2 victory.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Morocco, the first African World Cup representatives since 1934, also began strongly by taking the lead against the 1966 runners-up West Germany, but the Germans came back to win 2–1.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] West Germany also went behind against Bulgaria in their second match, but a Gerd Müller hat-trick helped them recover and win 5–2; the eventual Golden Boot winner Müller hit another hat-trick – the only hat-tricks of the entire tournament. – to win the group against Peru.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Mexico and the Soviet Union had finished tied at the top of Group 1 on both points and goal difference, meaning that the drawing of lots was required to rank them.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] On 12 June, the draw allocated the Soviet Union the group winners' berth, meaning that they would face Uruguay at the Estadio Azteca, while the host nation were paired against Italy in the smaller Toluca venue.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Mexican officials unsuccessfully appealed to FIFA to stage their game in the capital to avoid traffic problems.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The hosts took the lead against Italy with a José Luis González goal, but his teammate Javier Guzmán equalised with an own goal before half-time.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Italy then dominated the second half to progress to the semi-finals with a 4–1 win.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The Soviet Union were also eliminated in their quarter-final when a Víctor Espárrago header three minutes from the end of extra-time sent Uruguay through.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The Soviets had stopped play during Uruguay's attack leading to the goal, believing that the ball had crossed the touchline.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The all-South America tie in Guadalajara was the highest-scoring of the four quarter-finals as Brazil recorded a 4–2 triumph over Peru.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The match is considered to be one of the most entertaining matches in World Cup history: Brazil shot 27 times; Peru, 22.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Next came a rematch of the previous World Cup final between England and West Germany that took place in León.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The reigning champions took a two-goal lead, but Franz Beckenbauer halved the deficit when his low shot beat England's second-choice goalkeeper Peter Bonetti, who was playing after Gordon Banks suffered food poisoning the day before.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Eight minutes from time, an Uwe Seeler header levelled the score.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] England's Geoff Hurst then had an apparently legitimate goal ruled out for offside.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] An extra-time goal from Gerd Müller brought (West) Germany's first-ever competitive victory over England.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] All four of the semi-finalists were former world champions, with the line-up guaranteeing a final between Europe and South America.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] In the all-South American tie, controversially switched from the capital to the lower altitude of Guadalajara, Brazil came from behind to defeat Uruguay 3–1 and earn the right to contest their fourth World Cup Final.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Two Brazilian goals in the final 15 minutes decided a match that had been evenly-matched until that point.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The all-European meeting between Italy and West Germany produced a match regarded by many as one of the greatest World Cup games of all time.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Having led from the eighth minute through Roberto Boninsegna's strike, Italy were pegged back in injury time when sweeper Karl-Heinz Schnellinger scored his only international goal.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Extra-time brought five more goals as the lead swung between the two sides until Gianni Rivera gave the *Azzurri* a decisive 4–3 lead.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The match subsequently became known as the "Game of the Century", and today has a plaque outside the Estadio Azteca to commemorate it.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] West Germany went on to defeat Uruguay 1–0 in the match for third place.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] In the final, Brazil opened the scoring when Pelé headed in a cross from Rivellino in the 18th minute, but Roberto Boninsegna equalised for Italy after a series of blunders in the Brazilian defence.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The match remained level until the 65th minute when a powerful shot from Gérson restored the Brazilians' lead.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Further goals from Jairzinho and Carlos Alberto rewarded Brazil's attacking play and secured a 4–1 victory and a record third World Cup triumph, which earned them the right to permanently keep the Jules Rimet Trophy.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Both the Brazilian team that were crowned champions of the 1970 World Cup and the tournament itself have become regarded as among the very finest in the history of the FIFA World Cup.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] In contrast to the more physical style of play that had dominated the previous two tournaments, the 1970 Finals are noted for the attacking play adopted by most teams.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The officiating of the opening match, commentated by some media as overly strict, set a standard of discipline that instead helped protect skillful players in accordance with FIFA's stated wish.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The eventual champions Brazil, led by Carlos Alberto, and featuring Pelé, Clodoaldo, Gérson, Jairzinho, Rivellino, and Tostão, is often cited as the greatest-ever World Cup team.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] They won all of their six games on the way to the title, and had also won every one of their qualifying fixtures.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Jairzinho's feat of scoring in every finals match likewise has yet to be equalled.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Coach Mário Zagallo became the first man to win the World Cup as both a player (1958, 1962) and coach.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] This was the first World Cup to use the Telstar ball from Adidas (who have supplied every World Cup match ball to date), introduced as the "Telstar Erlast" for the 1968 European Football Championship.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The Telstar was the first World Cup ball to use the now-familiar truncated icosahedron for its design, consisting of 12 black pentagonal and 20 white hexagonal panels.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The 32-panel configuration had been introduced in 1962 by Select Sport, and was also used in the official logo for the 1970 World Cup.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The black-and-white pattern, to aid visibility on black and white television broadcasts (which was still commonplace then, as colour television was rare in many parts of the world), was also well established before the Telstar.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The name came from the Telstar communications satellite, which was roughly spherical and dotted with solar panels, somewhat similar in appearance to the football.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Forming a partnership with FIFA in 1970, Panini published its first FIFA World Cup sticker album for the 1970 World Cup, initiating a global craze for collecting and trading stickers.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] In 2017, a complete 1970 World Cup Panini sticker album signed by Pelé sold for a record £10,450.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The first round, or group stage, saw the 16 teams divided into four groups of four teams.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Each group was a round-robin of six games, where each team played one match against each of the other teams in the same group.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] Teams were awarded two points for a win, one point for a draw and none for a defeat.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The teams finishing first and second in each group qualified for the quarter-finals, while the bottom two teams in each group were eliminated from the tournament.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] The eight teams that had advanced from the group stage entered a single-elimination style tournament, which also featured a match for third place contested between the two losing semi-finalists.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] In this knockout stage (including the final), if a match was level at the end of 90 minutes, extra time of two periods (15 minutes each) would be played.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] In matches prior to the final, if the score was still level after extra time then a coin toss by the referee would determine the winner.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] If the final was still level after 120 minutes' play then the match would instead be replayed at a later date.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] With 10 goals, Gerd Müller was the top scorer in the tournament.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] In total, 95 goals were scored by 55 players, with only one of them credited as own goal.
[src:mexico/1970-fifa-world-cup] In 1986, FIFA published a report that ranked all teams in each World Cup up to and including 1986, based on progress in the competition, overall results and quality of the opposition.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The **1986 FIFA World Cup** was the 13th FIFA World Cup, the quadrennial football tournament for men's senior national teams.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] It was played in Mexico from 31 May to 29 June 1986.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The tournament was the second to feature a 24-team format.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Colombia had been originally chosen to host the competition by FIFA but, largely due to economic reasons, was not able to do so, and resigned in November 1982.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Mexico was selected as the new host in May 1983, and became the first country to host the World Cup more than once, after previously hosting the 1970 edition.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The World Cup was won by Argentina (their second title, after winning in 1978).
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Argentina was captained by the 25-year-old Diego Maradona, who played a large part in his team's success by scoring his "Hand of God" goal, as well as another voted the "Goal of the Century", in the same quarter-final match against England.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] These were two of the five goals that Maradona scored during the tournament, and he also created another five for his teammates.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Argentina beat West Germany 3–2 in the final at Mexico City's Estadio Azteca.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Argentina would not win the World Cup again until 2022, 36 years later.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Total attendance was 2,394,031, an average per match of 46,039.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Canada, Denmark and Iraq made their first appearances at the final stage.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The format of the competition changed from 1982.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The final pair of matches in each group started at the same time and the second round was played on a knockout basis rather than groups.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The 24 teams qualified were divided into six groups of four (A to F).
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The top two teams and the four best third-place finishers from the six groups advanced to the knockout round of 16 teams.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Italy were the defending champions, but were eliminated by France in the round of 16.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The tournament saw the appearance of the Mexican wave, a spectator phenomenon which was popularised worldwide after featuring during the tournament.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Colombia was originally chosen as hosts by FIFA in June 1974, with Bogotá, Medellín, Cali, Pereira and Bucaramanga intended as the host cities, plus potentially Barranquilla.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Colombia agreed to host a 16-team competition.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] However, days before the 1978 FIFA World Cup's opening match, FIFA later allowed an expansion to 24 teams for the 1982 World Cup in Spain, which was more challenging for Colombia to host, although FIFA President João Havelange initially gave assurances that they could revert to a 16-team tournament.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Colombian president Julio César Turbay Ayala was initially against holding the tournament in his country, but reluctantly granted permission in October 1980.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] However, the next Colombian president, Belisario Betancur, declared on 5 November 1982 that they could not afford to host the World Cup under the terms that FIFA demanded.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] On 20 May, the committee announced Mexico as the replacement hosts despite Havelange stating that the United States and Canada had made better presentations.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Mexico became the first nation to host two World Cups, as it had hosted the 1970 FIFA World Cup.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The Canadian representatives criticised the committee's decision not to consider Canada, saying they had submitted a more complete bid than Mexico, and that they had been misled by the number of stadiums required for bidding.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The United States' bid contained more than the required number of stadiums with the required capacity to host World Cup matches (at least 40,000 capacity, 60,000 for second-round matches and 80,000 for the tournament final).
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Mexico submitted a bid with 14 stadiums, only six of which seated over 40,000 at the time of the bid, and three over 60,000.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Havelange in turn criticised the United States' handling of stadium selection for the football tournament at the 1984 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The Americans also pointed out that Mexico had the influence of two seats on the 22-person executive committee, a FIFA vice president and an executive at Televisa, a Mexican television network with ties to Havelange.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Also working in Mexico's favour was Havelange secretly promising the broadcast rights to Televisa ahead of the vote.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] A severe earthquake in September 1985, eight months before the tournament, cast doubt over Mexico's ability to organise the event, but the stadiums were not affected and it was decided to go ahead with the preparations.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] As 1986 had been declared the International Year of Peace by the United Nations, the advertising boards of all the stadia displayed the FIFA and United Nations logos along with the legend "Football for Peace – Peace Year".
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] For the design of the logo an unofficial motto was adopted: "El Mundo Unido por Un Balón" ("The World United by a Ball").
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The final draw took place on 15 December 1985 hosted at Televisa San Ángel studios in Mexico City.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Three teams qualified for the World Cup for the first time: Canada, Denmark and Iraq.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Iraq played all their 'home' matches on neutral ground in Saudi Arabia because of the Iran–Iraq War.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Canada would not appear again until 2022, and Iraq would not qualify again until the next time the tournament was held in Mexico in 2026.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] South Korea qualified for the first time since 1954, Paraguay for the first time since 1958, Portugal for the first time since 1966, Morocco for the first time since 1970 and Bulgaria and Uruguay for the first time since 1974.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] It remains as of 2026 the last appearance of Hungary and Northern Ireland.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The following 24 teams qualified for the final tournament.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Eleven cities hosted the tournament, with a total of twelve stadiums used (two of them in Mexico City), among which were counted all five stadia that hosted the 1970 tournament.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The Azteca Stadium in Mexico City, the largest stadium used for the tournament, hosted nine matches (including the final), more than any other stadium used.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Mexico City hosted 13 total matches; the Olimpico Universitario Stadium hosted four matches (if the Mexico City suburban town Nezahualcoyotl's three matches are included, this brings the total up to 16 matches; nearly a third of all matches in this tournament).
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The hot, humid and rainy summer weather in Mexico varied from humid desert locations like Monterrey to tropical locations such as Guadalajara; but perhaps the greatest hardship the players had to contend with was the high altitude of the Mexican locations.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Mexico City, the location of the opening and final matches and the location where the most matches were played was 7,380 feet (2,250 m) above sea level and the weather there was not as hot as in other cities used in this World Cup.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] All of these venues except Monterrey were located in central Mexico, as this tournament was organized with the then-standard way of keeping teams playing in locations in close proximity to each other.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] All of the venues listed hosted knockout round matches except the ones in Nezahualcoyotl, Irapuato, Zapopan, Toluca and the Estadio Tecnologico in Monterrey.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] For a list of all squads that appeared in the final tournament, see *1986 FIFA World Cup squads*.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The first round of the finals began in Group A, where Italy were held 1–1 by Bulgaria.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Meanwhile, Argentina beat South Korea 3–1, with Diego Maradona playing a major part.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Italy and Argentina drew 1–1, Maradona and Alessandro Altobelli scoring.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] South Korea and Bulgaria also drew 1–1 in a downpour.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The final set of matches saw Argentina beating Bulgaria 2–0, and Italy narrowly defeating South Korea 3–2.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] In Group B Mexico beat Belgium 2–1, and despite being held 1–1 by Paraguay, they won the group after a further win over Iraq, 1–0.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Paraguay and Belgium also progressed after both beating Iraq and drawing with each other.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Group C pitted a strong Dynamo Kyiv-dominated Soviet Union side against the reigning European champions France.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] They drew with each other 1–1, with a goal scored by Vasyl Rats.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] France beat Canada 1–0 and finished in 2nd place in the group after beating Hungary, 3–0.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Hungary had earlier lost 6–0 against the Soviet Union, which won the group due to goal difference.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Group D saw Brazil start against Spain, winning 1–0 after the referee failed to validate a legal goal scored by Míchel.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Northern Ireland began their campaign with a draw against Algeria.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Northern Ireland were then narrowly beaten by Spain before losing to Brazil 3–0 in their final match.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] This match saw a goal from Josimar on his debut and was also the final time Pat Jennings played for Northern Ireland.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Spain qualified along with Brazil after defeating Algeria 3–0.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Denmark stormed through Group E, dubbed the group of death, with a 100 per cent record.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] They beat Alex Ferguson's Scotland 1–0 in their first game, then hammered Uruguay 6–1, with Preben Elkjær hitting a hat-trick.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Denmark beat one of the favourites to win the tournament, West Germany, 2–0 thanks to a Jesper Olsen penalty and a goal from John Eriksen.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] After losing to Denmark, Scotland took the lead against West Germany thanks to a Gordon Strachan goal, but the West Germans fought back to win 2–1.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] After a violent 0–0 draw against Uruguay, the Scots were eliminated from the tournament.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] During that game José Batista of Uruguay was sent off after less than one minute of play for a foul on Strachan, a World Cup record that still stands.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] West Germany went through to the second round despite a loss against Denmark.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Morocco topped Group F after holding both Poland and England to goalless draws, and beating Portugal 3–1.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] By doing so, they became the first African team, and only the second nation from outside Europe and the Americas (after North Korea in 1966), to reach the second round.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] In their last first-round game, with the captaincy taken over by Peter Shilton in goal, a first-half Gary Lineker hat-trick helped the reshaped side beat Poland 3–0 – although losing yet another player to a ban for the next round, Terry Fenwick receiving his second booking of the tournament.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Poland had previously beaten Portugal, and in the end the Portuguese were the only team from Group F to be eliminated in the first round.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Portugal, making their first appearance in 20 years, went on strike (in the Saltillo Affair) during the competition.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Players refused to train between their first and second games (against England and Poland) and were eliminated after a loss to Morocco in the final group match.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Belgium beat the Soviet Union 4–3, despite a hat-trick by the Soviets' Igor Belanov.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The game was level at 2–2 after 90 minutes, and in extra time Stephane Demol and Nico Claesen put Belgium 4–2 up.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Belanov scored from the penalty spot with nine minutes remaining, but neither he nor any of his teammates could find a fourth goal for the Soviet Union.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] At the Olympic University Stadium in Mexico City, the European champions France ended Italy's reign as world champions with a 2–0 victory thanks to goals from Michel Platini and Yannick Stopyra.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] In the rematch of the 1930 FIFA World Cup Final, Argentina just edged out South American champions Uruguay in Puebla thanks to a 42nd-minute strike from Pedro Pasculli.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The all-South American affair had a Diego Maradona goal disallowed.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] In Querétaro, Denmark were eliminated as they went from a 1–0 lead to a 5–1 battering against Spain; key player Frank Arnesen was suspended for the game after being sent off against West Germany in their last group match, for taking a swipe at German playmaker Lothar Matthäus.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The Danes scored first, with a Jesper Olsen penalty, but they were then taken apart by a devastating performance from Butragueño of Spain, who scored four of his team's five goals.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] At the Azteca Stadium in Mexico City, England progressed to the quarter-finals comfortably when they saw off Paraguay 3–0, while Brazil brushed aside Poland 4–0.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] West Germany had a much harder time getting past Morocco, for whom goalkeeper Badou Zaki had an outstanding game.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Morocco held out until the 87th minute, when Lothar Matthäus scored the only goal of the match with a free kick.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Mexico won 2–0 against Bulgaria with an outstanding scissor-kick goal by Manuel Negrete which is honored by a remembrance plaque at the Azteca.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] In the quarter-finals, France faced three-time world champion Brazil in Guadalajara.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Brazil were well on top in the early stages, and Careca put them one up after 18 minutes.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Five minutes before half-time, France drew level when Michel Platini scored his 41st goal after converting a cross from Dominique Rocheteau.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Brazil had a chance to regain the lead in the second half when Branco was fouled by French keeper Joël Bats in the penalty area.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Zico got up to take the kick, but Bats saved Zico's penalty.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The match went to extra time, and France finished slightly the stronger of the two sides.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] No more goals were scored, and so it was time for a penalty shoot-out.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Socrates, who had earlier missed an open goal and headed an easy chance straight into the French keeper's arms, failed with the first kick for Brazil.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The next six penalties were all converted, and then Platini fired over the bar.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Brazil were back on level terms – but not for long.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Julio Cesar struck the post with his penalty, and Luis Fernández then scored to put France through 4–3 on penalties.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Two other quarter-finals were also decided on penalties.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Jan Ceulemans put Belgium ahead against Spain in the 35th minute, but Spanish substitute Señor equalised with five minutes to go.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] No more goals were scored in extra time, and Belgium won the shoot-out 5–4.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] On the hosts' first game outside of the Azteca, Francisco Javier Cruz saw a goal disallowed as West Germany and Mexico drew 0–0 after extra time.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The West Germans eliminated the hosts 4–1 on penalties.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] As a curiosity, the German goalkeeper Harald Schumacher jumped to the right in the three Mexican penalties (stopping two of them).
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The quarter-final between Argentina and England at the Azteca featured two very different goals in the second half by Diego Maradona: the first was scored illegally, as he punched the ball into the goal past England goalkeeper Peter Shilton.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The referee did not see the handball and the goal was given as valid.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] After the game, Maradona claimed the goal was scored "A bit with the head of Maradona and another bit with the hand of God"; it became known as the "Hand of God" goal.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] For his second goal, voted "Goal of the Century" in 2002 on the FIFA website, Maradona dribbled half the length of the field past five English players before scoring.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] In Argentina, the game was seen as revenge for the Falklands War.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] In the first semi-final match, Andreas Brehme put West Germany 1–0 ahead against France in the ninth minute in Guadalajara, but the outcome remained in doubt until two minutes from time when Rudi Völler made it 2–0, and West Germany were in the final for the second World Cup in succession.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] In the second semi-final match, Maradona struck twice in the second half as Argentina beat Belgium 2–0 at the Azteca.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] France went on to defeat Belgium in the match for third place, 4–2.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] So it was to be the South American Argentina vs the European West Germany at the final at the Azteca, the second time this massive stadium would host a World Cup Final (the first in 1970).
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Jose Brown put Argentina one up midway through the first half of the final, and when Jorge Valdano scored a second for the South Americans in the 55th minute, Argentina looked to be strolling to victory.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] West Germany then staged a spirited comeback.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Karl-Heinz Rummenigge pulled one back in the 74th minute, and six minutes later Rudi Völler hit the equaliser.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] With seven minutes remaining, a pass from Maradona gave Jorge Burruchaga the chance to score the winner for Argentina.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Eight years on from their home triumph, Argentina regained the world title and 30 million people in Argentina celebrated in the streets after the final victory.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Maradona was the Golden Ball winner as the best player of the tournament, while Gary Lineker of England won the Golden Boot as the leading scorer of the World Cup with six goals.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Argentina beat West Germany for the first time and won their second World Cup.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Belgium finished in fourth place, their best finish in the World Cup until 2018, where they finished third.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Gary Lineker received the Golden Boot for scoring six goals.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] In total, 132 goals were scored by 82 players, with two of them credited as own goals.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The sponsors of the 1986 FIFA World Cup consisted out of 15 FIFA World Cup sponsors.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The official mascot of the 1986 World Cup was *Pique*, a jalapeño pepper, characteristic of Mexican cuisine, with a moustache, a Colimote sombrero, and Mexican football team colours.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] Its name comes from *picante*, a Spanish word meaning "spicy", and was also a pun on the "PK" abbreviation of the football term penalty kick.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The character caused a degree of controversy within Mexico for its ethnic stereotypes.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The official match ball of this World Cup was the "Azteca", manufactured by Adidas.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] It was the first fully synthetic FIFA World Cup ball and the elaborately decorated design was inspired by the hosting nation’s native Aztec architecture and murals.
[src:mexico/1986-fifa-world-cup] The official song of this World Cup was "El mundo unido por un balón".
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] General elections were held in Mexico on Sunday, 2 July 2000.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] Voters went to the polls to elect a new president to serve a single six-year term, replacing President Ernesto Zedillo Ponce de León, who was ineligible for re-election under the 1917 Constitution.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] The presidential election was won by Vicente Fox of the Alliance for Change, who received 43.4% of the vote, the first time the opposition had won an election since the Mexican Revolution.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] In the congressional elections the Alliance for Change emerged as the largest faction in the Chamber of Deputies with 224 of the 500 seats, whilst the Institutional Revolutionary Party remained the largest faction in the Senate with 60 of the 128 seats in the Senate.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] Voter turnout was between 63 and 64% in the elections.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] This historically significant election made Fox the first president elected from an opposition party since Francisco I.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] Madero in 1911, as well as the first in 71 years to defeat, with 43 percent of the vote, the then-dominant Institutional Revolutionary Party.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] President Ernesto Zedillo sought to break away from the 71-year-old PRI succession ritual, so the PRI conducted an unprecedented internal process to choose its presidential candidate for the 2000 elections.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] The president declared, "The so-called *dedazo* is dead"; *dedazo* being the term used to refer to the president personally choosing his successor, which roughly translates to "handpicking".
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] Francisco Labastida Ochoa, Humberto Roque Villanueva, Manuel Bartlett and Roberto Madrazo were the pre-candidates.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] Despite the president's statement, there was still a sense that Labastida was most likely to become the official candidate due to being the closest to President Zedillo.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] Madrazo's confrontation with Labastida during the election was notable, as was Madrazo's "challenging" stance toward Zedillo, exemplified by his campaign slogan, *Dale un Madrazo al dedazo* ("Give a Madrazo to the *dedazo*", though it could also be translated as "Give a blow to the handpicking").
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] On 7 November 1999 the primary election was held, and widespread reports of fraudulent tactics were present.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] Nevertheless, Madrazo accepted the election's outcome and rejoined the Tabasco government following a meeting with Labastida in Los Pinos, where Zedillo intervened to stop Madrazo from breaking with the PRI.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] On 20 November Labastida was declared the PRI candidate.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] The former Guanajuato governor Vicente Fox Quesada was the only person to seek the National Action Party nomination and was ratified by the party.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] Pedro Cerisola was his general campaign coordinator.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] Porfirio Muñoz Ledo and Cuauhtémoc Cárdenas declared their interest in being candidates for the Party of the Democratic Revolution (PRD), a contest that ended with Muñoz Ledo's dismissal from the party.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] According to Muñoz Ledo it was inevitable that the same person would run for office a third time if there was no "true democratic process" in the PRD.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] Muñoz Ledo was later confirmed as the candidate for the Authentic Party of the Mexican Revolution and Cárdenas was designated as the PRD candidate.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] On 27 April 2000 PAN candidate Vicente Fox sent a letter containing ten points to the apostolic nuncio Leonardo Sandri and the Conference of the Mexican Episcopate, outlining the measures he pledged to take on behalf of the Catholic Church and other Christian churches should he win the presidency.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] Fox reaffirmed his strong religious stance and identified himself as a devout Catholic.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] Even though Fox had finally won the presidency, the promises he made to the churches in that letter were not kept given that the PAN failed to secure an absolute majority in the Congress of the Union.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] The *Reforma* newspaper, which had predicted a Labastida victory in every poll they published during the campaign, attributed their mistake to the so-called "fear factor".
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] Some isolated incidents of irregularities and problems were reported.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] For example, one irregularity in the southern state of Campeche involved the European Union electoral observer Rocco Buttiglione and could have created problems for President Ernesto Zedillo had the PRI candidate won.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] Civic organizations fielded more than 80,000 trained electoral observers, foreign observers were invited to witness the process, and numerous "quick count" operations and exit polls (not all of them independent) validated the official vote tabulation.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] The largest exit poll was organized by the U.S. firm Penn, Schoen & Berland, financed by a Dallas-based organization called Democracy Watch with the support of the Vicente Fox campaign, who were concerned about possible election fraud.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] Numerous electoral reforms implemented after the widely-derided and fraudulent 1988 election opened up the Mexican political system, and since then opposition parties have made historic gains in elections at all levels.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] The chief electoral concerns shifted from outright fraud to campaign fairness issues and, between 1995 and 1996, the political parties negotiated constitutional amendments to address these issues.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] The legislation implemented included major points of consensus that had been worked out with the opposition parties.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] Under the new laws, public financing predominated over private contributions to political parties, procedures for auditing parties were tightened, and the authority and independence of the electoral institutions were strengthened.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] The court system was also given greatly expanded authority to hear civil rights cases on electoral matters brought by individuals or groups.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] In short, the extensive reform efforts of the 1990s "leveled the playing field" for the parties.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] On election night, exit polls and preliminary results from the Federal Electoral Institute quickly proclaimed PAN candidate Vicente Fox winner.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] PRI candidate Francisco Labastida then headed to his party's headquarters to give his concession speech, but just minutes before he was to speak, a message from President Ernesto Zedillo was broadcast on national TV, in which the President himself acknowledged Fox's victory and congratulated him.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] The fact that the concession first came from the President instead of his party's candidate later caused tensions between Zedillo and Labastida.
[src:mexico/2000-mexican-general-election] Fox was sworn-in as president on 1 December, ending 71 years of PRI rule.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Human presence in Mexico dates back to at least 11,500 BC, although dates as old as 28,000 BC have been proposed for less securely dated sites.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Mesoamerica, considered a cradle of civilization, was home to numerous advanced societies, including the Olmecs, Maya, Zapotecs, Teotihuacan civilization, and Purépecha.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Spanish colonization began in 1521 with an indigenous alliance that defeated the Aztec Empire, establishing the colony of New Spain with its capital at Tenochtitlan, now Mexico City.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] New Spain became a major center of the transoceanic economy during the Age of Discovery, fueled by silver mining and its position as a hub between Europe and Asia.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] This gave rise to one of the largest multiracial populations in the world.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The Peninsular War led to the 1810–1821 Mexican War of Independence, which ended Peninsular rule and led to the creation of the First Mexican Empire, which quickly collapsed into the short-lived First Mexican Republic.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In 1848, Mexico lost nearly half its territory in the Mexican-American War.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Liberal reforms set in the Constitution of 1857 led to civil war and French intervention, culminating in the establishment of the Second Mexican Empire under Emperor Maximilian I of Habsburg, who was overthrown by Republican forces led by Benito Juárez.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The late 19th century saw the long dictatorship of Porfirio Díaz, whose modernization policies came at the cost of severe social unrest.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The 1910–1920 Mexican Revolution led to the overthrow of Díaz and the adoption of the 1917 Constitution.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Mexico experienced rapid industrialization and economic growth in the 1940s–1970s, amidst electoral fraud, the Tlatelolco massacre, and economic crises.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The late 20th century saw a shift towards neoliberalism, marked by the signing of the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) in 1994, amidst unrest in Chiapas.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Mexico is a federal republic with a presidential system of government, characterized by a democratic framework and the separation of powers into three branches: executive, legislative, and judicial.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The federal legislature consists of the bicameral Congress of the Union, comprising the Chamber of Deputies, which represents the population, and the Senate, which provides equal representation for each state.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The Constitution establishes three levels of government: the federal Union, the state governments, and the municipal governments.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Mexico's federal structure grants autonomy to its 32 states, and its political system is deeply influenced by indigenous traditions and European Enlightenment ideals.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Mexico is a newly industrialized and developing country, with the world's 15th-largest economy by nominal GDP and the 13th-largest by purchasing power parity (PPP).
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] It ranks first in the Americas and seventh in the world by the number of UNESCO World Heritage Sites.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] It is one of the world's 17 megadiverse countries, ranking fifth in natural biodiversity.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] It is a major tourist destination: as of 2022, it is the sixth most-visited country in the world, with 42.2 million international arrivals.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Mexico's large economy and population, global cultural influence, and steady democratization make it a regional and middle power, increasingly identifying as an emerging power.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] As with much of Latin America, poverty, systemic corruption, and crime remain widespread.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Since 2006, approximately 127,000 deaths have been caused by ongoing conflict between drug trafficking syndicates.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The country's official name has changed as the form of government has changed.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The declaration of independence signed on 6 November 1813 by the deputies of the Congress of Anáhuac called the territory *América Septentrional* (Northern America).
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The 1821 Plan of Iguala also used *América Septentrional*.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] On two occasions (1821–1823 and 1863–1867), the country was known as *Imperio Mexicano* (Mexican Empire).
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] All three federal constitutions (1824, 1857, and 1917, the current constitution) used the name *Estados Unidos Mexicanos*—or the variant *Estados-Unidos Mexicanos*, all of which have been translated as "United Mexican States".
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The phrase *República Mexicana*, "Mexican Republic", was used in the 1836 Constitutional Laws.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In the Nahuatl version of the current constitution, the official name is *Mexika Sentik Wexteyowalko*, and in its Yucatec Maya version, *U Múuchꞌ Péetluꞌumiloꞌob México*.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In fact, by virtue of the legal equality of Spanish with the 68 indigenous languages of the country, all have their own translation of the official name.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The earliest human artifacts in Mexico are chips of stone tools found in the Valley of Mexico, dated to circa 10,000 years ago.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Mexico is the site of the domestication of maize, tomato, and beans, which produced an agricultural surplus.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] This enabled the transition from paleo-Indian hunter-gatherers to sedentary agricultural villages beginning around 5000 BC.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Villages became more densely populated, socially stratified with an artisan class, and developed into chiefdoms.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The most powerful rulers had religious and political power, organizing the construction of ceremonial centers.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The earliest complex civilization was the Olmec culture, which flourished on the Gulf Coast from around 1500 BC.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Olmec cultural traits diffused through Mexico into other formative-era cultures in Chiapas, Oaxaca, and the Valley of Mexico.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In the pre-classical period, the Maya and Zapotec civilizations developed complex centers.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The first true Mesoamerican writing systems were developed in the Epi-Olmec and Zapotec cultures.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The Mesoamerican writing tradition reached its height in the Classic Maya Hieroglyphic script, the earliest written histories date from then.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The tradition of writing was important after Spanish conquest in 1521, with indigenous scribes learning to write their languages in alphabetic letters, while continuing to create pictorial texts.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In Central Mexico, the height of the classic period saw the ascendancy of Teotihuacán, which formed a military and commercial empire.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Teotihuacan, with a population of more than 150,000, had some of the largest pyramidal structures in the pre-Columbian Americas.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] After the collapse of Teotihuacán around 600 AD, competition ensued between political centers in such as Xochicalco and Cholula.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] During the Epi-Classic, Nahua peoples began moving south into Mesoamerica, and became politically and culturally dominant in central Mexico.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] During 1000–1519 AD, central Mexico was dominated by the Toltec culture, Oaxaca by the Mixtec, and the lowland Maya area had centers at Chichén Itzá and Mayapán.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Toward the end of the post-Classic period, the Aztecs established dominance, establishing a political and economic empire based in Tenochtitlan (modern Mexico City), extending from central Mexico to Guatemala.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Although the Spanish Empire established colonies in the Caribbean in 1493, it first learned of Mexico during the Juan de Grijalva expedition of 1518.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The Spanish conquest of the Aztec Empire began in 1519 when Hernán Cortés founded Veracruz.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The 1521 capture of Tenochtitlan and posterior founding of Mexico City on its ruins, was the beginning of a 300-year colonial era, during which Mexico was known as *Nueva España* (New Spain).
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Two factors made Mexico a jewel in the Empire: the existence of large, hierarchically organized Mesoamerican populations that rendered tribute and performed obligatory labor, and discovery of silver deposits in north Mexico.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The Kingdom of New Spain was created from the remnants of the Aztec empire.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The two pillars of Spanish rule were the State and Church, both under the authority of the Spanish crown.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In 1493 the pope granted sweeping powers to the Spanish monarchy for its overseas empire, with the proviso it spread Christianity.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In 1524, King Charles I created the Council of the Indies based in Spain to oversee State power in its colonies.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The crown established a high court in Mexico City, the *Real Audiencia* ('royal audience').
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In 1535, the crown appointed the first Viceroy of New Spain, the highest official of the State.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The Diocese of Mexico, created in 1530, was elevated to the Archdiocese of Mexico in 1546, with an archbishop as its head.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Castilian Spanish was the language of the rulers.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Catholic faith was the only one permitted, with non-Catholics and Catholics, excluding Indians, holding unorthodox views subject to the Mexican Inquisition.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Spanish military forces, sometimes accompanied by native allies, led expeditions to conquer territory or quell rebellions.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Notable Amerindian revolts include the Chichimeca War (1576–1606), the Tepehuán Revolt (1616–20), and Pueblo Revolt (1680).
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Most rebellions were small-scale, posing no major threat to the elites.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] To protect Mexico from the attacks of English, French, and Dutch pirates and the Crown's monopoly of revenue, only two ports were open to foreign trade—Veracruz on the Atlantic, connecting to Spain, and Acapulco on the Pacific, connecting to the Philippines.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Pirate attacks included the 1663 Sack of Campeche and 1683 Attack on Veracruz.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Of greater concern to the crown was the issue of invasion, especially after Britain seized Havana and Manila in 1762, during the Seven Years' War.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] It created a standing military, increased coastal fortifications, and expanded the northern presidios and missions into Alta California.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The volatility of the urban poor in Mexico City was evident in the 1692 riot over the price of maize.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] It escalated to a full-scale attack on the seats of power, with the viceregal palace and archbishop's residence attacked.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In 1810, secular priest Miguel Hidalgo y Costilla declared against "bad government" in Dolores, Guanajuato.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Known as the Cry of Dolores (Spanish: *Grito de Dolores*) it is commemorated each year, on 16 September, as Mexico's independence day.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The upheaval in the Empire, that resulted in the independence of most of its New World territories, was due to Napoleon's invasion of Spain in 1808.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Hidalgo and some of his soldiers were executed by firing squad in 1811.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The first 35 years after Mexico's independence were marked by instability and changing of the Mexican state from a transient monarchy to a fragile federated republic.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] There were military coups, foreign invasions, ideological conflict between Conservatives and Liberals, and economic stagnation.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Former Royal Army General Agustín de Iturbide became regent, as newly independent Mexico sought a constitutional monarch from Europe.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] When no member of a European royal house desired the position, Iturbide himself was declared Emperor Agustín I.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The US was the first country to recognize Mexico's independence, sending a message to Europe via the Monroe Doctrine not to intervene in Mexico.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The emperor's rule was short (1822–23), he was overthrown by army officers in the Plan of Casa Mata.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Central America and Chiapas left the union to form the Federal Republic of Central America.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In 1824, the First Mexican Republic was established.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Former insurgent General Guadalupe Victoria became the first president — the first of many generals to hold the presidency.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In 1829, former insurgent general and fierce Liberal Vicente Guerrero, a signatory of the Plan of Iguala that achieved independence, became president in a disputed election.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] During his term, from April to December 1829, he abolished slavery.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] His Conservative vice president, former Royalist General Anastasio Bustamante, led a coup against him and Guerrero was judicially murdered.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Mexico's ability to maintain its independence and establish a viable government was in question.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Spain attempted to reconquer it during the 1820s, but eventually recognized its independence.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] France attempted to recoup losses it claimed for its citizens during Mexico's unrest and blockaded the Gulf Coast during the Pastry War of 1838–39.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] General Antonio López de Santa Anna emerged as a national hero because of his role in these conflicts; Santa Anna came to dominate politics for the next 25 years, often known as the "Age of Santa Anna", until his overthrow in 1855.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Mexico contended with indigenous groups that controlled the territory that Mexico claimed in the north.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] For example, the Comanche controlled a huge territory in sparsely populated central and northern Texas.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Wanting to stabilize and develop that area — and as few from central Mexico had chosen to resettle to this remote and hostile territory — the Mexican government encouraged Anglo-American immigration into present-day Texas, a region that bordered the US.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Mexico by law was a Catholic country; the Anglo-Americans were primarily Protestant English speakers from the southern US.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Some brought their black slaves, which after 1829 was contrary to Mexican law.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In 1835, Santa Anna sought to centralize government rule in Mexico, suspending the 1824 constitution and promulgating the Seven Laws, which placed power in his hands.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Three new governments declared independence: the Republic of Texas, the Republic of the Rio Grande and the Republic of Yucatán.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The largest blow to Mexico was the US invasion in 1846 in the Mexican–American War.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Mexico lost much of its northern territory, sealed in the 1848 Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Despite this, Santa Anna returned to the presidency, but was ousted and exiled during the Liberal Revolution of Ayutla.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The overthrow of Santa Anna, and establishment of a civilian government by liberals, allowed them to enact laws they considered vital for development.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] La Reforma attempted to modernize the economy and institutions along liberal principles.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] They promulgated a new Constitution of 1857, separating Church and State, stripping the Church and military of privileges (*fueros*); mandating the sale of Church-owned property and indigenous community lands, and secularizing education.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Conservatives revolted, touching off the Reform War between Liberal and Conservative governments (1858–61).
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The Liberals defeated the Conservative army on the battlefield, but Conservatives sought to gain power via intervention by the French, asking Emperor Napoleon III to place a European monarch as head of state in Mexico.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The French Army defeated the Mexicans and placed Maximilian Habsburg on the newly established throne, supported by Mexican Conservatives.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The Liberal Republic under Benito Juárez was a government in internal exile, but with the end of the American Civil War in 1865, the US government began aiding the Mexican Republic.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The French Army withdrew its support, but Maximilian remained in Mexico; Republican forces executed him.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The "Restored Republic" saw the return of Juárez, "the personification of the embattled republic," as president.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The Conservatives had been defeated militarily and discredited politically, for their collaboration with the French, and liberalism became synonymous with patriotism.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Notable was Porfirio Díaz, a hero of the *Cinco de Mayo*, who sought civilian power and challenged Juárez on his re-election in 1867.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Díaz then rebelled but was crushed by Juárez.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Having won re-election, Juárez died in office in 1872.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Liberal Sebastián Lerdo de Tejada became president, declaring a "religion of the state" for the rule of law, peace, and order.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] When Lerdo ran for re-election, Díaz rebelled against the civilian president, issuing the Plan of Tuxtepec.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Díaz had more support and waged guerrilla war against Lerdo.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] On the verge of Díaz's victory on the battlefield, Lerdo fled from office into exile.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] After the turmoil of 1810 to 1876, the 35-year rule of Liberal General Porfirio Díaz (1876–1911) allowed Mexico to modernize in a period described one of "order and progress".
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The Porfiriato was characterized by economic stability and growth, foreign investment and influence, an expansion of the rail network and telecommunications, and investments in the arts and sciences.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Díaz ruled with a group of advisors that became known as the *científicos* ('scientists').
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The regime was influenced by positivism.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] They rejected theology and idealism in favor of scientific methods applied towards development.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] An integral aspect was secular education.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The Díaz government led a protracted conflict against the Yaqui that culminated with the forced relocation of Yaqui to Yucatán and Oaxaca.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Díaz gave an interview where he said he was not going to run in the 1910 elections, when he would be 80.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Opposition had been suppressed and there were few avenues for new leaders.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] His announcement set off a frenzy of activity, including the unlikely candidacy of the son of a rich landowning family, Francisco I.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Madero won a surprising amount of support when Díaz changed his mind and ran in the election, jailing Madero.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In February 1913, a military coup overthrew Madero's government, with the support of the US, resulting in Madero's murder by agents of Federal Army General Victoriano Huerta.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The US administration of Taft supported the Huerta coup, but when Democrat Woodrow Wilson was inaugurated as president in March 1913, Wilson refused to recognize Huerta's regime and allowed arms sales to the Constitutionalists.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Wilson ordered troops to occupy the strategic port of Veracruz in 1914.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] A coalition of anti-Huerta forces in the North, the Constitutional Army led by Governor of Coahuila Venustiano Carranza, and a peasant army in the South under Emiliano Zapata defeated the Federal Army in 1914, leaving only revolutionary forces.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Following the revolutionaries' victory against Huerta, they sought to broker a political solution, but the coalition splintered, plunging Mexico again into civil war.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Constitutionalist general Pancho Villa broke with Carranza and allied with Zapata.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Carranza's best general Alvaro Obregón defeated Villa, his former comrade, in the Battle of Celaya in 1915, and Villa's forces melted away.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Carranza became president, and the US recognized his government while Zapata's forces in the south reverted to guerrilla war.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] After Villa was defeated by revolutionary forces in 1915, he led an incursion raid into Columbus, New Mexico, prompting the US to send 10,000 troops in an unsuccessful attempt to capture Villa.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Carranza pushed back against US troops being in northern Mexico.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The expeditionary forces withdrew as the US entered World War I.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In 1916, the winners of the Mexican revolution met at a constitutional convention to draft the Constitution of 1917, ratified in February 1917.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The Constitution empowered the government to expropriate resources including land, gave rights to labor, and strengthened anticlerical provisions.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] It remains the governing document of Mexico.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The revolutionary war killed 900,000 out of Mexico's 15 million population.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Consolidating power, Carranza had Zapata assassinated in 1919.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Carranza had gained the support of the peasantry, but once in power, he did little to institute land reform, which had motivated many to fight.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Carranza returned some confiscated land to their original owners.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Carranza's best general, Obregón, served in his administration, but returned to his home state Sonora to position himself to run in the 1920 election.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Since Carranza could not run for re-election, he chose a civilian to succeed him, intending to remain in power behind the presidency.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Obregón and two other Sonoran revolutionary generals drew up the Plan of Agua Prieta, overthrowing Carranza.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] General Adolfo de la Huerta became interim president, followed by the election of General Álvaro Obregón.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The post-revolutionary period (1920–46) was characterized by revolutionary generals serving as presidents, including Álvaro Obregón (1920–24), Plutarco Elías Calles (1924–28), Lázaro Cárdenas (1934–40), and Manuel Avila Camacho (1940–46).
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The government sought to bring order, end military intervention in politics, and create organizations of interest groups.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Workers, peasants, office workers, and even the army for a short period, were incorporated as sectors of the single party that dominated politics from its founding in 1929.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Obregón instigated land reform and strengthened organized labor.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] He gained recognition from the US and settled claims with companies and individuals that lost property during the Revolution.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] He imposed his fellow revolutionary general, Calles, as his successor.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Calles provoked a major conflict with the Catholic Church and Catholic guerrilla armies when he enforced anticlerical articles of the constitution, which ended with an agreement.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Although the constitution prohibited the reelection of the president, Obregón wished to run again and the constitution was amended to allow non-consecutive re-election.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] He won the 1928 elections but was assassinated by a Catholic activist, causing a succession crisis.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Calles could not become president again, so he sought to set up a structure to manage succession, founding the Institutional Revolutionary Party, which dominated Mexico for the rest of the 20th century.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Despite not holding the presidency, Calles remained the key politician during the period known as the Maximato (1929–34), that ended during the presidency of Lázaro Cárdenas, who expelled Calles and implemented economic and social reforms.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] This included the Mexican oil expropriation in 1938, which nationalized the U.S. and Anglo-Dutch oil company known as the Mexican Eagle Petroleum Company, which would result in the creation of the state-owned Pemex.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Cárdenas's successor, Manuel Ávila Camacho (1940–46) was moderate, and relations between the US and Mexico improved during World War II, when Mexico was a significant ally.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] From 1946 the election of Miguel Alemán, the first civilian president in the post-revolutionary period, Mexico embarked on a program of development, known as the Mexican miracle, characterized by industrialization, urbanization, and increased inequality between urban and rural areas.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The Green Revolution, a technological movement that led to worldwide increases in crop production, began in the Yaqui Valley in the middle of the 20th century.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] With robust growth, Mexico sought to showcase itself by hosting the 1968 Summer Olympics.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The government poured resources into new facilities, prompting unrest among students and others.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Demonstrations in Mexico City went on for weeks before the opening of the games, with the government of Gustavo Díaz Ordaz cracking down.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The culmination was the Tlatelolco Massacre, which killed 300-800 protesters.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Although the economy continued to flourish for some, inequality remained a factor of discontent.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] PRI rule became authoritarian and oppressive in the Mexican Dirty War.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In the 1980s the first cracks emerged in the PRI's political dominance.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In Baja California, the PAN candidate was elected governor.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] When De la Madrid chose Carlos Salinas de Gortari as the candidate for the PRI, and therefore a foregone presidential victor, Cuauhtémoc Cárdenas, son of former President Lázaro Cárdenas, broke with the PRI and challenged Salinas in the 1988 elections.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In 1988 there was electoral fraud, with results showing that Salinas had won the election by the narrowest percentage ever.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] There were protests in Mexico City over the stolen election.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Salinas took the oath of office in December 1988.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In 1990 the PRI was described by Mario Vargas Llosa as the "perfect dictatorship", but there had been major challenges to the PRI's hegemony.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The armed conflict was short-lived and continues as a non-violent opposition movement against neoliberalism and globalization.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In 1994, following the assassination of the PRI's presidential candidate Luis Donaldo Colosio, Salinas was succeeded by victorious PRI candidate Ernesto Zedillo.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Salinas left Zedillo's government to deal with the Mexican peso crisis, requiring a $50 billion IMF bailout.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Macroeconomic reforms were started by Zedillo, and the economy recovered and growth peaked at 7% by 1999.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] After 71 years of rule, the incumbent PRI lost the 2000 presidential election to Vicente Fox of the opposing conservative National Action Party (PAN).
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In the 2006 presidential election, Felipe Calderón from the PAN was declared the winner, with a narrow margin (0.6%) over leftist politician Andrés Manuel López Obrador of the Party of the Democratic Revolution (PRD).
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] López Obrador, however, contested the election and pledged to create an "alternative government".
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In the 2012 presidential election, the PRI again won the presidency with the election of Enrique Peña Nieto.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] However, he won with a plurality of around 38% and did not have a legislative majority.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] During the 21st century, Mexico has contended with high crime rates, bureaucratic corruption, narcotrafficking, and a stagnant economy.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Many state-owned enterprises were privatized starting in the 1990s with neoliberal reforms.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Pemex, the state-owned petroleum company is being privatized, with exploration licenses being issued.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In a push against corruption, the ex-CEO of Pemex, Emilio Lozoya Austin, was arrested in 2020.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] After founding the new political party MORENA, Andrés Manuel López Obrador (known as AMLO) won the 2018 election with over 50%.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] His coalition, led by his left-wing party founded after the 2012 elections, included parties from across the spectrum.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The coalition won a majority in the upper and lower Congress chambers.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] His success is attributed to opposing political forces exhausting their chances, as well as AMLO's adoption of moderate discourse focused on reconciliation.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The first confirmed case of COVID-19 in Mexico occurred in February 2020, and COVID-19 vaccination in Mexico began in December.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Claudia Sheinbaum, AMLO's successor, won the 2024 presidential election in a landslide and became the first woman to lead Mexico.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Mexico is located between latitudes 14° and 33°N, and longitudes 86° and 119°W in the southern portion of North America, with a total area of 1,972,550 km2 (761,606 sq mi), is the 13th largest country by total area.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] It has coastlines on the Pacific Ocean and Gulf of California, as well as the Gulf of Mexico and Caribbean Sea, the latter two forming part of the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Within these seas are about 6,000 km2 (2,317 sq mi) of islands.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Almost all of Mexico lies in the North American Plate, with small parts of the Baja California peninsula on the Pacific and Cocos Plates.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Geophysically, some geographers include the territory east of the Isthmus of Tehuantepec (around 12% of the total) within Central America.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Geopolitically, Mexico is entirely considered part of North America.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Two mountain ranges known as Sierra Madre Oriental and Sierra Madre Occidental, which are the extension of the Rocky Mountains from northern North America crossed the country from north to south and a fourth mountain range, the Sierra Madre del Sur, runs from Michoacán to Oaxaca.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The Mexican territory is prone to volcanism.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Mexico has nine distinct regions: Baja California, the Pacific Coastal Lowlands, the Mexican Plateau, the Sierra Madre Oriental, the Sierra Madre Occidental, the Cordillera Neovolcánica, the Gulf Coastal Plain, the Southern Highlands, and the Yucatán Peninsula.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] An important geologic feature of the Yucatán peninsula is the Chicxulub crater, the scientific consensus is that the Chicxulub impactor was responsible for the Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Although Mexico is large (a little over 2,000 mi (3,219 km) in length from its farthest land points), much of its land mass is incompatible with agriculture due to aridity, soil, or terrain.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In 2018, an estimated 54.9% of land was agricultural; 11.8% was arable; 1.4% was in permanent crops; 41.7% was permanent pasture; and 33.3% was forest.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Mexico is irrigated by several rivers, with the longest being the Rio Grande, which serves as a natural eastern border with the United States.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The Usumacinta River serves as a natural southern border between Mexico and Guatemala.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The climate of Mexico is varied due to the country's size and topography.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The Tropic of Cancer effectively divides the country into temperate and tropical zones.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Land north of the Tropic of Cancer experiences cooler temperatures during the winter months.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] South of the Tropic of Cancer, temperatures are fairly constant year-round and vary solely as a function of elevation.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] This gives Mexico one of the world's most diverse weather systems.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Maritime air masses bring seasonal precipitation from May until August.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Many parts of Mexico, particularly the north, have a dry climate with only sporadic rainfall, while parts of the tropical lowlands in the south average more than 2,000 mm (78.7 in) of annual precipitation.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] For example, many cities in the north like Monterrey, Hermosillo, and Mexicali experience temperatures of 40 °C (104 °F) or more in summer.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In the Sonoran Desert temperatures reach 50 °C (122 °F) or more.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Most of the country's territory has a temperate to dry climate.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Areas south of the Tropic of Cancer with elevations up to 1,000 m (3,281 ft), the southern parts of both coastal plains as well as the Yucatán Peninsula, have a yearly median temperature between 24 and 28 °C (75.2 and 82.4 °F).
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Temperatures here remain high throughout the year, with only a 5 °C (9 °F) difference between winter and summer median temperatures.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] The Pacific coast is subject to natural hazards such as tsunamis and both Mexican coasts with the exception of the south coast of the Bay of Campeche and northern Baja California are vulnerable to serious hurricanes during the summer and fall.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Although low-lying areas north of the Tropic of Cancer are hot and humid during the summer, they generally have lower yearly temperature averages (from 20 to 24 °C or 68.0 to 75.2 °F) because of more moderate conditions during the winter.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Climate change in Mexico is causing widespread impacts including rising temperatures, altered precipitation patterns, intensified hurricanes, and sea-level rise in coastal regions.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] These changes pose threats to water resources and agriculture (particularly for rural and smallholder farmers), and affect crops including maize and coffee, contributing to economic insecurity.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Climate change is impacting Mexicans' health, exacerbating human migration, and increasing extinction risk for Mexico's biodiversity, as protected areas are expected to face warming temperatures and decreased precipitation.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Mexico ranks fourth in the world in biodiversity and is one of the 17 megadiverse countries.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] With over 200,000 species, Mexico is home of 10–12% of the world's biodiversity.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Mexico ranks first in biodiversity in reptiles with 707 known species, second in mammals with 438 species, fourth in amphibians with 290 species, and fourth in flora, with 26,000 species.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Mexico is also considered the second country in the world in ecosystems and fourth in overall species.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] About 2,500 species are protected by Mexican legislation.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In 2002, Mexico had the second fastest rate of deforestation in the world, second only to Brazil.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] It had a 2019 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 6.82/10, ranking it 63rd globally out of 172 countries.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] According to SGI there is Deforestation and soil erosion especially in rural areas of Mexico.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In the 2022 report it was noted environmental protection laws have improved in major cities but remain unenforced or unregulated in rural regions.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] In Mexico, 170,000 square kilometers (65,637 sq mi) are considered "Protected Natural Areas".
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] These include 34 biosphere reserves, 67 national parks, 4 natural monuments, 26 areas of protected flora and fauna, 4 areas for natural resource protection and 17 sanctuaries (zones rich in diverse species).
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Some of Mexico's native culinary ingredients include maize, tomato, beans, squash, chocolate, vanilla, avocado, guava, chayote, epazote, camote, jícama, nopal, zucchini, tejocote, huitlacoche, sapote, mamey sapote, and a great variety of chiles, such as the habanero and the jalapeño.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Tequila, the distilled alcoholic drink made from cultivated agave cacti is a major industry.
[src:mexico/mexico-p01] Because of its high biodiversity Mexico has also been a frequent site of bioprospecting by international research bodies.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The United Mexican States is a federation whose government is representative, democratic, and republican based on a presidential system according to the 1917 Constitution.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The federal legislature is the bicameral Congress of the Union, composed of the Senate of the Republic and the Chamber of Deputies.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The Congress makes federal law, declares war, imposes taxes, approves the national budget and international treaties, and ratifies diplomatic appointments.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The federal Congress, as well as the state legislatures, are elected by a system of parallel voting that includes plurality and proportional representation.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The Chamber of Deputies has 500 deputies.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Of these, 300 are elected by plurality vote in single-member districts (the federal electoral districts) and 200 are elected by proportional representation with closed party lists for which the country is divided into five electoral constituencies.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The Senate comprises 128 senators: 64 (two for each state and two for Mexico City) are elected by plurality vote in pairs, 32 are the first minority or first-runner-up (one for each state and one for Mexico City), and 32 are elected by proportional representation from national closed party lists.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The executive is the President of the United Mexican States, who is the head of state and government, as well as the commander-in-chief of the Mexican military forces.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The President also appoints the Cabinet and other officers.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The President is responsible for executing and enforcing the law and has the power to veto bills.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The highest organ of the judicial branch of government is the Supreme Court of Justice, the national supreme court.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Judges, pre-selected by Congress, are elected by popular vote.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The nine members of the Supreme Court are elected for a single twelve-year term.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The first judicial election occurred in 2025.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The Supreme Court of Justice interprets laws and judges cases of federal competency.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Other institutions of the judiciary are the Federal Electoral Tribunal, collegiate, unitary, and district tribunals, and the Judicial Disciplinary Tribunal.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The National Regeneration Movement (Morena), a left-wing populist party, has been the ruling party since 2018, and it won a second term in the 2024 general election.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Democratic backsliding starting around 2019 was found by the V-Dem Democracy Report.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The boundaries and constituent units of Mexico evolved from its colonial-era origins.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Central America peacefully separated from Mexico after independence in 1821.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Yucatán was briefly an independent republic.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Texas separated in the Texas Revolution and when it was annexed to the U.S. in 1845, it set the stage for the Mexican–American War and major territorial loss to the U.S.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The sale of northern territory known in the U.S. as the Gadsden Purchase was the last loss of Mexican territory.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The United Mexican States is a federation of 31 free and sovereign states, which form a union that exercises a degree of jurisdiction over Mexico City.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Each state has its constitution, congress, and a judiciary, and its citizens elect by direct voting a governor for a six-year term, and representatives to their respective unicameral state congresses for three-year terms.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexico City is a special political division that belongs to the federation as a whole and not to a particular state.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Formerly known as the Federal District, its autonomy was previously limited relative to that of the states.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] It dropped this designation in 2016 and is in the process of achieving greater political autonomy by becoming a federal entity with its constitution and congress.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The states are divided into municipalities, the smallest administrative political entity in the country, governed by a mayor or municipal president (*presidente municipal*), elected by its residents by plurality.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The foreign relations of Mexico are directed by the President of Mexico and managed through the Ministry of Foreign Affairs.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Since the 1930s, the Estrada Doctrine has served as a crucial complement to these principles.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexico is a founding member of several international organizations, most notably the United Nations, the Organization of American States, the Organization of Ibero-American States, the OPANAL and the CELAC.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In 2008, Mexico contributed over 40 million dollars to the United Nations regular budget.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In addition, it was the only Latin American member of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development since it joined in 1994 until Chile gained full membership in 2010.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexico is considered a regional power hence its presence in major economic groups such as the G8+5 and the G-20.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Since the 1990s Mexico has sought a reform of the United Nations Security Council and its working methods with the support of Canada, Italy, Pakistan and other nine countries, which form a group informally called the Coffee Club.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] It has an observer status at the Council of Europe.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The Mexican Armed Forces are administered by the Secretariat of National Defense (*Secretaria de Defensa Nacional*, SEDENA).
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] There are two branches: the Mexican Army (which includes the Mexican Air Force) and Mexican Navy.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The National Guard, which was formed in 2019 from the disbanded Federal Police and military police of the Army and Navy, functions as a gendarmerie; while responsible for law enforcement, it is placed under military command.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Figures vary, but as of 2024, there are approximately 220,000 armed forces personnel: 160,000 Army; 10,000 Air Force; and 50,000 Navy, including about 20,000 marines.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The National Guard has roughly 110,000 personnel.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Military expenditures are a small fraction of GDP, at around 0.6% as of 2023.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Since the 1990s, when the military escalated its role in the war on drugs, increasing importance has been placed on acquiring airborne surveillance platforms, aircraft, helicopters, digital war-fighting technologies, urban warfare equipment and rapid troop transport.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexico has the capabilities to manufacture nuclear weapons, but abandoned this possibility with the Treaty of Tlatelolco in 1968, pledging to use its nuclear technology only for peaceful purposes.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexico signed the UN treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Historically, Mexico has remained neutral in international conflicts, with the exception of World War II.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] However, in recent years some political parties have proposed an amendment of the Constitution to allow the Mexican Army, Air Force or Navy to collaborate with the United Nations in peacekeeping missions, or to provide military help to countries that officially ask for it.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The Mexican Federal Police was dissolved in 2019 by a constitutional amendment during the administration of President López Obrador, being replaced by the National Guard, a national gendarmerie formed from units and assets of the Federal Police, Military Police, and Naval Police.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] As of 2022, the National Guard numbered 110,000 personnel.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] López Obrador had increasingly used military forces for domestic law enforcement, particularly against drug cartels.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] There have been serious abuses of power reported in security operations in the southern part of the country and in indigenous communities and poor urban neighborhoods.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The National Human Rights Commission has had little impact in reversing this trend, engaging mostly in documentation but failing to use its powers to issue public condemnations to the officials who ignore its recommendations.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Most Mexicans have low confidence in the police or the judicial system, and therefore, few crimes are actually reported by the citizens.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] There have been public demonstrations of outrage against what is considered a culture of impunity.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexico has fully recognized same-sex marriage since 2022, and anti-discrimination laws regarding sexual orientation have existed in the nation since 2003.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] However, hate crimes towards the LGBT community remain an issue in Mexico.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Other crime and human rights violations in Mexico have been criticized, including enforced disappearances (kidnappings), abuses against migrants, extrajudicial killings, gender-based violence, especially femicide, and attacks on journalists and human rights advocates.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] A 2020 report by the BBC gives statistics on crime in Mexico, with 10.7 million households with at least one victim of crime.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] As of May 2022, 100,000 people are officially listed as missing, most since 2007 when President Calderón attempted to stop the drug cartels.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Drug cartels remain a major issue in Mexico, with a proliferation of smaller cartels when larger ones are broken up and increasingly the use of more sophisticated military equipment and tactics.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexico's drug war, ongoing since 2006, has left over 120,000 dead and perhaps another 37,000 missing.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexico's National Geography and Statistics Institute estimated that in 2014, one-fifth of Mexicans were victims of some sort of crime.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The mass kidnapping of 43 students in Iguala on 26 September 2014 triggered nationwide protests against the government's weak response to the disappearances and widespread corruption that gives free rein to criminal organizations.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] More than 100 journalists and media workers have been killed or disappeared since 2000, and most of these crimes remained unsolved, improperly investigated, and with few perpetrators arrested and convicted.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In August 2025, demonstrations were held all around Mexico, in protest over the 130,000 people who have disappeared and considered missing since 2007.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] As of April 2026, Mexico has the 13th largest economy by purchasing power parity (PPP) (US$3.5 trillion), and a GDP per capita of US$26,643.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The World Bank reported in 2026 that the country's gross national income in was the second highest in Latin America after Brazil at US$1.8 trillion.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexico has the sixth largest electronics industry after China, the US, Japan, South Korea, and Taiwan.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexico is the second-largest exporter of electronics to the US where it exported $71 billion worth of electronics in 2011.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Electronics exports grew 73% between 2002 and 2012.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The manufactured value-added sector, which electronics is part of, accounted for 18% of GDP.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexico produces the most automobiles of any North American nation.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The industry produces technologically complex components and engages in research and development.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The "Big Three" (General Motors, Ford and Chrysler) have been operating in Mexico since the 1930s, while Volkswagen and Nissan built their plants in the 1960s.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In Puebla alone, 70 industrial part-makers cluster around Volkswagen.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In 2016 Kia opened a $1 billion factory in Nuevo León, with Audi also opening an assembling plant in Puebla the same year.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] BMW, Mercedes-Benz and Nissan currently have plants in construction.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The domestic car industry is represented by DINA S.A., which has built buses and trucks since 1962, and the new Mastretta company that builds the high-performance Mastretta MXT sports car.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In 2006, trade with the US and Canada accounted for almost 50% of Mexico's exports and 45% of its imports.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] During the first three quarters of 2010, the United States had a $46 billion trade deficit with Mexico.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The remittances from Mexican citizens working in the US are significant; after dipping during the 2008 Great Recession and the COVID-19 pandemic in 2021 they are topping other sources of foreign income.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Remittances are directed to Mexico by direct links from a U.S. government banking program.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Although multiple international organizations coincide and classify Mexico as an upper middle income country, or a middle class country, Mexico's National Council for the Evaluation of Social Development Policy (CONEVAL), reports that much of Mexico's population lives in poverty.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] From 2008 to 2010 the portion who live in poverty rose from 44.5% to 46.2% (from 48.8 to 52 million people).
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] According to the OECD's poverty line (defined as the percentage of the population who earns 60% or less of the national median income) 20% of Mexico's population lived in poverty in 2019.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Among OECD countries, Mexico has the second-highest degree of inequality between the extremely poor and rich, after Chile– though it is one of few countries in which this has been falling.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The bottom ten percent in the income hierarchy disposes of 1.4% of the country's resources, whereas the upper ten percent dispose of 36%.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The OECD notes that Mexico's budgeted expenses for poverty alleviation and social development are only about a third of the OECD average.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] This is also reflected in infant mortality in Mexico, which is three times higher than the OECD average, whereas its literacy is in the median range.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] According to a 2008 report the average income in an urban area of Mexico was $27,000, while in rural areas just miles away was, it only $8,000.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Daily minimum wages are set annually; it was set at $315.04 Mexican pesos (US$17.20) in 2026 ($440.87 in the country's northern border), making it comparable to Costa Rica, Uruguay, Chile.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] This rapidly increased, as it was set at 88 pesos in 2018.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The telecommunications industry is mostly dominated by Telmex (*Teléfonos de México*), previously a government monopoly privatized in 1990.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] By 2006, Telmex had expanded its operations to Colombia, Peru, Chile, Argentina, Brazil, Uruguay, and the United States.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Other players are Axtel, Maxcom, Alestra, Marcatel, AT&T Mexico.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mobile telephony has the advantage of reaching all areas at a lower cost, and the total number of mobile lines is almost two times that of landlines, with an estimation of 97 million lines.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The telecommunication industry is regulated by the government through Cofetel (*Comisión Federal de Telecomunicaciones*).
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The satellite system is domestic and operates 120 earth stations.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] There is extensive microwave radio relay network and considerable use of fiber-optic and coaxial cable.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexican satellites are operated by *Satélites Mexicanos* (Satmex), a private company, leader in Latin America and servicing North and South America.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Energy production is managed by the state-owned companies Federal Commission of Electricity and Pemex.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Pemex, the public company in charge of exploration, extraction, transportation, and marketing of crude oil and natural gas, as well as the refining and distribution of petroleum products and petrochemicals, is one of the largest companies in the world by revenue, making US$86 billion sales per year.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexico is the sixth-largest oil producer, with 3.7 million barrels per day.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In 1980 oil exports accounted for 62% of total exports; by 2000 it was only 7%.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexico owns 7 oil refineries on its territory, with the newest built in 2022 and another refinery within the US.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexico has 60 hydroelectric power plants which generate 12% of the country's electricity, the largest is the 2,400 MW Manuel Moreno Torres Dam on the Grijalva River, the world's fourth most productive hydroelectric plant.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexico has the third-largest solar power potential estimated at 5kWh/m2 daily, which corresponds to 50 times the national electricity generation.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] There is over 1 million square meters of solar thermal panels installed, while in 2005 there were only 115,000 square meters of solar PV (photo-voltaic) panels.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The project SEGH-CFE 1 located in Puerto Libertad, Sonora in the Northwest of Mexico was completed in 2018 and has a capacity of 46.8 MW from an array of 187,200 solar panels, all of its generated electricity is sold directly to the CFE and absorbed into the utility's transmission system.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The Villanueva solar park in Coahuila which opened in 2019, is the largest solar power plant in the Americas with a capacity of 828 MW.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexico has one nuclear power plant, the Laguna Verde Nuclear Power Station located in the state of Veracruz and numerous wind farms, with the largest wind farm in Latin America located in Oaxaca.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Although Mexico has increased its renewable electricity generation from wind and solar sources, it is still dependent on fossil fuels for most of its energy.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In 2023 Mexico was in the top 15 highest greenhouse gas emitters, contributing over 5 million tonnes, or 1.4% of the global total.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexico has committed to reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 35% by 2030, with an increased target of 40% conditional upon external support.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The country aims to cut black carbon emissions by 51% unconditionally and 70% with additional support by 2030 and has committed to net zero by 2050.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The National Autonomous University of Mexico was officially established in 1910, and the university became one of the most important institutes of higher learning in Mexico.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] UNAM provides world class education in science, medicine, and engineering.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Many scientific institutes and new institutes of higher learning, such as National Polytechnic Institute, were established during the first half of the 20th century.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Most of the new research institutes were created within UNAM.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Twelve institutes were integrated into UNAM from 1929 to 1973.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In 1959, the Mexican Academy of Sciences was created to coordinate scientific efforts between academics.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Molina shared the Nobel Prize in Chemistry with Paul J.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Sherwood Rowland for their work in atmospheric chemistry, particularly concerning the formation and decomposition of ozone.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Molina, an alumnus of UNAM, became the first Mexican citizen to win the Nobel Prize in science.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The largest scientific project being developed in Mexico was the construction of the Large Millimeter Telescope (Gran Telescopio Milimétrico, GMT), the world's largest and most sensitive single-aperture telescope in its frequency range.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] It was designed to observe regions of space obscured by stellar dust.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexico was ranked 58th in the Global Innovation Index in 2025.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] As of 2017, Mexico was the 6th most visited country.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] It had the 15th highest income from tourism and highest in Latin America.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The vast majority of tourists come from the US and Canada, followed by Europe and Asia.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] A smaller number come from other Latin American countries.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In the 2017 Travel and Tourism Competitiveness Report, Mexico was ranked 22nd in the world, and 3rd in the Americas.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The coastlines are rich in sunny stretches of beach.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] According to the Constitution of Mexico Article 27, the entirety of the coastlines is under federal ownership.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] On the Yucatán peninsula, one of the most popular beach destinations is the resort town of Cancún, especially among university students during spring break.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] To the south of Cancun is the coastal strip called Riviera Maya which includes the beach town of Playa del Carmen and the ecological parks of Xcaret and Xel-Há.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] To the south of Cancún is the town of Tulum, notable for its ruins of Maya civilization.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Other tourist destinations include Acapulco with crowded beaches and multi-story hotels on the shores.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] At the southern tip of the Baja California peninsula is the resort town of Cabo San Lucas, noted for its marlin fishing.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Closer to the US border is the weekend draw of San Felipe, Baja California.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In Mexican cities along the Mexico–United States border, the most lucrative hospitality industry is now medical tourism, with remnants of the traditional motivations that drove tourists to Mexico's northern borderlands for nearly a century.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Dominant medical tourism for tourism planning are the purchase of medication, dentistry, elective surgery, optometry, and chiropractic.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Despite its difficult topography, Mexico's roadway is extensive and most areas are covered.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The road network has an extent of 366,095 km (227,481 mi), of which 116,802 km (72,577 mi) are paved, making it 9th largest of any country.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Of these, 10,474 km (6,508 mi) are multi-lane expressways: 9,544 km (5,930 mi) are four-lane highways and the rest have 6 or more lanes.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexico was one of the first Latin American countries to promote railway development, and the network covers 30,952 km (19,233 mi).
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The Secretary of Communications and Transport of Mexico proposed a high-speed rail link that will transport its passengers from Mexico City to Guadalajara, Jalisco.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The train, which will travel at 300 kilometers per hour (190 miles per hour), will allow passengers to travel from Mexico City to Guadalajara in just 2 hours.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The whole project was projected to cost 240 billion pesos, or about 25 billion US$ and is being paid for jointly by the Mexican government and the local private sector including one of the wealthiest men in the world, Mexico's billionaire business tycoon Carlos Slim.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexico has 233 airports with paved runways; of these, 10 carry 72% of national cargo and 97% of international cargo.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The Mexico City International Airport remains the busiest in Latin America and the 36th busiest in the world transporting 45 million passengers a year.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Two additional airports operate simultaneously to help relieve congestion from the Mexico City International Airport: the Toluca International Airport and the Felipe Ángeles International Airport.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In 2022, Mexico's estimated population was 129,150,971 people, per the National Geography and Statistics Institute.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In 2025, Mexico's population was estimated by the UN to have grown to 131,946,900 people.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Since at least the 1970s, Mexico has been the most populous Spanish-speaking country in the world.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Throughout the 19th century, the population of Mexico barely doubled.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] This trend continued in the first two decades of the 20th century.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In 1900, the Mexican population was a little more than 13 million.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] 1910–1920) greatly impacted population growth, with the 1921 census reporting a loss of about 1 million inhabitants.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The growth rate increased dramatically between the 1930s and the 1980s.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexico had growth rates of over 3% between 1950 and 1980.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The Mexican population doubled in twenty years, and at that rate, it was expected that by 2000 there would be 120 million people living in Mexico.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexico's population grew from 70 million in 1982 to 123.5 million inhabitants in 2017.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Life expectancy increased from 36 years in 1895, to 75 years in 2020.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In 2020, there were 48 metropolitan areas in Mexico, in which close to 53% of Mexico's population lives.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The most populous metropolitan area in Mexico is the *Metropolitan Area of the Valley of Mexico*, or Greater Mexico City, which in 2020 had a population of 21.8 million, or around 18% of the nation's population.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The next four largest metropolitan areas are Greater Monterrey (5.3 million), Greater Guadalajara (5.2 million), Greater Puebla (3.2 million) and Greater Toluca (2.3 million).
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Urban areas contain 76.81% of Mexico's population.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexico's population is diverse, and ethnic research has historically felt the impact of nationalist discourses on identity.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Social stratification and racism in Mexico have remained in the contemporary era.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Although phenotype is not as important as culture, European features and lighter skin tone are favored by middle- and upper-class groups.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Starting with the Royal Decree of 1503 and the Laws of Burgos of 1512, the Spanish crown influenced by the School of Salamanca recognized the freedom of the indigenous peoples of the Americas, while simultaneously importing African slaves.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Indian republics were granted some degree of autonomy, and full assimilation of Spaniards and Indians was ordained.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In practice, the Spanish often occupied the administrative positions, and maintained a fluid and complicated caste-like system which favored Europeans over other groups.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] This social stratification offered some degree of social mobility, as Afro-Mexicans and indigenous people assimilated to the *mestizo* (mixed) caste, and even pure Spaniards could also fall off the economic ladder.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Slavery was abolished twice by the insurgent movements of Hidalgo and Morelos in 1810, and again by the independent government of Vicente Guerrero in 1829, an Afro-Mexican.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] After Mexico gained independence from Spain in 1821, any traces of the colonial caste system were abandoned, with race being omitted from public documents.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Near the end of the 1800s, the government led by Porfirio Díaz adopted policies of selective immigration from Europe and persecuted certain indigenous groups, as it was believed it would help to modernize the country.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] While people of mixed ancestry form the most prominent ethnic group in contemporary Mexico, the subjective and ever-changing definition of this category means that precise estimates are impossible.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] During Mexican Revolution, and again during the Cárdenas presidency, government efforts were made to decrease social and economic inequality among indigenous Mexicans.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In 1992, the Article 2 of the Constitution of Mexico was amended to define Mexico as a pluricultural country and specifically to emphasize the role of indigenous Mexicans.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] This new legal framework preceded the Zapatista Army of National Liberation's push against the mestizaje ideology that led to the 1996 San Andrés Accords which granted autonomy, recognition, and rights to the indigenous population of Mexico.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] At Mexico's 2020 census, 19.4% of the population identified as indigenous and 6.1% of Mexico's population speaks an Indigenous language.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Since the 1960s there has been a cultural and academic re-evaluation of the role of Afro-Mexicans in Mexico, dispelling the misconception that they had assimilated into the mestizo identity.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] At the 2020 census, Afro-Mexicans were 2.04% of Mexico's population.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In 2020, Asians and Middle Easterners were around 1% of the population each.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In 2019, an estimated 11.7 million Mexicans lived outside Mexico, in addition to 13.5 million born abroad and another 12 million descendants.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The vast majority of this combined population (98–99%) are in the U.S.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The largest Mexican communities outside Mexico are in the metropolitan areas of Los Angeles, Chicago, Houston and Dallas–Fort Worth.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Between 1965 and 2015, more than 16 million Mexicans migrated to the United States alone—by far the top destination for both temporary and permanent migration—representing one of the largest mass migrations in modern history.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] As a result of these major migration flows in recent decades, an estimated 37.2 million U.S. residents, or 11.2% of the US population, identified as being of full or partial Mexican ancestry.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In 2018, among the remaining 2% of Mexican expatriates not residing in the U.S., the most popular destinations are Canada (86,780), primarily the provinces of Ontario and Quebec, followed by Spain and Germany.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The latter two countries account for two-thirds of all Mexicans living in Europe.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Historically, and relative to other countries in the Western Hemisphere, Mexico has not been a destination of mass migration.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In 2020, an estimated 1.2 million foreigners settled in Mexico, up from nearly 1 million in 2010.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In 2021, Mexico officially received 68,000 new immigrants, a 16% increase from the prior year.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The overall number of migrants, including those unauthorized to enter or stay in the country, may be higher than official figures.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The vast majority of migrants in Mexico come from the United States (900,000), making Mexico the top destination for U.S. citizens abroad.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The second largest group comes from neighboring Guatemala (54,500), followed by Spain (27,600).
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Other major sources of migration are fellow Latin American countries, which include Colombia (20,600), Argentina (19,200) and Cuba (18,100).
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Communities descended from the Lebanese diaspora and German-born Mennonites have had an outsized impact in Mexico's culture, particularly in its cuisine and traditional music.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Spanish is the *de facto* national language spoken by the vast majority of the population, making Mexico the world's most populous Hispanophone country.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexican Spanish refers to the varieties of Spanish spoken in Mexico, which differs from one region to another in sound, structure, and vocabulary.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The federal government recognizes sixty-eight linguistic groups and 364 varieties of indigenous languages.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In 2015, an estimated 8.3 million citizens spoke these languages.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Nahuatl is spoken by more than 1.7 million, followed by Yucatec Maya, used daily by nearly 850,000 people.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Tzeltal and Tzotzil, two other Mayan languages, are spoken by around half a million people each, primarily in the southern state of Chiapas.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mixtec and Zapotec, with an estimated 500,000 native speakers each, are two other prominent language groups.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] That notwithstanding, in practice, indigenous peoples often face discrimination and do not have full access to public services such as education and healthcare, or to the justice system, as Spanish is the prevailing language.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The Chipilo dialect, a variant of the Venetian language, is spoken in the town of Chipilo, located in the central state of Puebla, by around 2,500 people, mainly descendants of Venetians that migrated to the area in the late 19th century.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] English is the most commonly taught foreign language in Mexico.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] It is estimated that nearly 24 million, or around a fifth of the population, study English through public schools, private institutions, or self-access channels.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] However, in 2015, a high level of English proficiency was limited to 5% of the population.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] French is the second most widely taught foreign language.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Every year, between 200,000 and 250,000 Mexican students enroll in French language courses.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Although the Constitutions of 1857 and 1917 put limits on the role of the Catholic Church in Mexico, Catholicism remains Mexico's dominant religious affiliation.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] 8.1% (9,488,671) of the population declared having no religion.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The 97,864,218 Catholics of Mexico constitute in absolute terms the second largest Catholic community in the world, after Brazil's.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In 1997, 47% percent of them attended church services weekly.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Pentecostalism is the second Christian creed in Mexico, with more than 1.3 million adherents.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Migratory phenomena have led to the spread of different aspects of Christianity, including branches Protestants, Eastern Catholic Churches and Eastern Orthodox Church.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In the 2020 census, there were 58,876 Jews in Mexico.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The presence of Jews in Mexico dates back to the 16th century when Spaniards arrived in the Americas.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] The modern Jewish Community began to be formed in the late 19th and early 20th century when Jews from Europe and the Ottoman Empire immigrated to Mexico due to instability and antisemitism.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Islam in Mexico, with 7,982 members, is practiced mostly by Arab Mexicans.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In the 2020 census, 36,764 Mexicans belonged to a spiritualist religion, a category which includes a tiny Buddhist population.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] About 74,000 people practiced religions with "ethnic roots", religions of mostly African and indigenous origin.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] There is often a syncretism between shamanism and Catholic traditions.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Another religion of popular syncretism in Mexico, especially in recent years, is Santería, mainly due to the large number of Cubans who settled in Mexico after the Cuban Revolution.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] One of the most exemplary cases of popular religiosity is the cult of Holy Dead (Santa Muerte).
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Other examples are the representations of the Passion of Christ and the celebration of Day of the Dead, which take place within the framework of the Catholic Christian imagery, but under a very particular reinterpretation.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In 2020, the literacy rate in Mexico was 95.25%, a slight increase from 94.86% in 2018, and significantly higher than 82.99% in 1980.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Literacy between males and females is relatively equal.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] According to most rankings, the publicly funded National Autonomous University of Mexico (UNAM) is the best university in the country.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Other prominent public universities include the National Polytechnic Institute, the Metropolitan Autonomous University, the University of Guadalajara and the Autonomous University of Nuevo León and El Colegio de México.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In terms of private academic institutions, among the most highly ranked is the Monterrey Institute of Technology and Higher Education.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Other prominent private universities include Universidad Iberoamericana, Universidad Panamericana, ITAM and Universidad Anáhuac.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] In the 1930s, Mexico made a commitment to rural health care, mandating that mostly urban medical students receive training in it and to make them agents of the state to assess marginal areas.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Since the early 1990s, Mexico entered a transitional stage in the health of its population and some indicators such as mortality patterns are identical to those found in highly developed countries like Germany or Japan.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Mexico's medical infrastructure is highly rated for the most part and is usually excellent in major cities.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Rural communities still lack equipment for advanced medical procedures, forcing patients in those locations to travel to the closest urban areas to get specialized medical care.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Social determinants of health can be used to evaluate the state of health in Mexico.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] State-funded institutions such as Mexican Social Security Institute (IMSS) and the Institute for Social Security and Services for State Workers (ISSSTE) play a major role in health and social security.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Private health services are also very important and account for 13% of all medical units in the country.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Medical training is done mostly at public universities, with many specializations done in vocational or internship settings.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Some public universities in Mexico, such as the University of Guadalajara, have signed agreements with the U.S. to receive and train American students in medicine.
[src:mexico/mexico-p02] Health care costs in private institutions and prescription drugs in Mexico are on average lower than that of its North American economic partners.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Mexican culture reflects a long and complex history of interactions between various peoples through migration, conquest, and trade.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Three centuries of Spanish rule resulted in the blending of Spanish culture with those of different indigenous groups.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] However, a high degree of stratification along the lines of class, ethnicity, and race perpetuated distinct subcultures.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] The Porfirian era (*el Porfiriato*) (1876–1911), which brought relative peace after four decades of civil unrest and war, saw the development of philosophy and art, often with government support.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Since that time, as accentuated during the Mexican Revolution, the government adopted and promoted the *mestizo* ideology to create a unified Mexican identity, characterized by the blending of different races and cultures.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] In light of the ethnicities that formed the Mexican people, José Vasconcelos in *La Raza Cósmica* (The Cosmic Race) (1925) defined Mexico and Latin America to be the melting pot of all races (thus extending the definition of the *mestizo*) not only biologically but culturally as well.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Other Mexican intellectuals grappled with the idea of *Lo Mexicano*, which seeks "to discover the national ethos of Mexican culture." Nobel laureate Octavio Paz explores the notion of a Mexican national character in *The Labyrinth of Solitude*.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Painting is one of the oldest arts in Mexico.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Cave painting in Mexican territory is about 7,500 years old and has been found in the caves of the Baja California Peninsula.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Pre-Columbian Mexican art is present in buildings and caves, in Aztec codices, in ceramics, in garments, etc.; examples of this are the Maya mural paintings of Bonampak or the murals found in Teotihuacán, Cacaxtla and Monte Albán.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Mural painting with Christian religious themes had an important flowering during the 16th century, early colonial era in newly constructed churches and monasteries.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Examples can be found in Acolman, Actopan, Huejotzingo, Tecamachalco and Zinacantepec.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] As with most art during the early modern era in the West, colonial-era Mexican art was religious during the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Starting in the late seventeenth century, and, most prominently in the eighteenth century, secular portraits and images of racial types, so-called *casta* painting appeared.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Important painters of the late colonial period were Juan Correa, Cristóbal de Villalpando and Miguel Cabrera.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] In early post-independence Mexico, nineteenth-century painting had a marked romantic influence; landscapes and portraits were the greatest expressions of this era.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Hermenegildo Bustos is one of the most appreciated painters of the historiography of Mexican art.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Other painters include Santiago Rebull, Félix Parra, Eugenio Landesio, and his noted pupil, the landscape artist José María Velasco.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] In the 20th century artists such as Diego Rivera, David Alfaro Siqueiros, and José Clemente Orozco, the so-called "Big Three" of Mexican muralism achieved worldwide recognition.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] They were commissioned by the Mexican government to paint large-scale historical murals on the walls of public buildings, which helped shape popular perceptions of the Mexican Revolution and Mexican cultural identity.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Frida Kahlo's largely personal portraiture is considered by many as the most important historical work by a female artist.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] In the 21st century, Mexico City became home to the highest concentration of art museums in the world.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Institutions like the Museo Jumex, the largest collection of its kind, founded by collector Eugenio López Alonso and bolstered by art advisor Esthella Provas, changed the notion of contemporary art in Latin America.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] The Museo Tamayo Arte Contemporaneous founded by Rufino Tamayo is also considered a preeminent institution and introduced foreign artists to a wider population.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] The country is also an epicenter for International art galleries including Kurimanzutto and FF Projects, and leading artists including Gabriel Orozco, Bosco Sodi, Stefan Brüggemann, and Mario García Torres.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] The architecture of Mesoamerican civilizations evolved in style from simple to complex.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Teotihuacan, designated a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1987, is one of the foremost examples of ancient pyramid construction.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] The cities of the Maya stand out to modern architects as examples of integration between large urban centers (with elaborate stone construction) and a thick jungle, generally with a complex network of roads.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Pre-Columbian Mesoamerica also saw distinctive architectural influences from the Olmec, the Puuc and oasiamerican peoples.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] With the arrival of the Spanish, architectural theories of the Greco-Latin order with Arab influences were introduced.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] In the first few decades of Spanish presence in the continent, the high level of Christian missionary activity, especially by mendicant orders like the Dominicans or Franciscans, meant the construction of many monasteries, often with Romanesque, Gothic or Mudéjar elements.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] The interaction between Spaniards and Indigenous people gave rise to artistic styles such as the *tequitqui*, from the Nahuatl term for worker or builder.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Years later, Baroque and Mannerist styles prevailed in large cathedrals and civil buildings.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] In rural areas, *haciendas* or stately estates with Mozarabic tendencies were built.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] In the 19th century, the neoclassical movement arose as the country gained independence and sought to establish itself as a republic.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] A famous example is the Hospicio Cabañas, an orphanage and hospital complex completed in 1829.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] The *art nouveau*, and the *art deco* were styles introduced into the design of the Palacio de Bellas Artes to mark the identity of the Mexican nation with Greek-Roman and pre-Columbian symbols.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] As a new sense of nationalism developed in the 20th century, a strengthened central government issued formal policies that sought to use architecture to show Mexico's modernity and differentiation from other nations.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] The development of Mexican modernist architecture was especially manifested in the mid-1950s construction of the Ciudad Universitaria, Mexico City, the main campus of the National Autonomous University of Mexico.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Designed by the most prestigious architects of the era, including Mario Pani, Eugenio Peschard, and Enrique del Moral, the buildings feature murals by artists Diego Rivera, David Alfaro Siqueiros, and José Chávez Morado.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] It has since been recognized as a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Juan O'Gorman was one of the first environmental architects in modern Mexico to develop the "organic" theory, trying to integrate buildings onto the landscape within the same approaches of Frank Lloyd Wright.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] In the search for a new architecture that does not resemble the styles of the past, it achieves a joint manifestation with the mural painting and the landscaping.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Luis Barragán combined the shape of the space with forms of rural vernacular architecture of Mexico and Mediterranean countries (Spain-Morocco), integrating color that handles light and shade in different tones and opens a look at the international minimalism.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] He won the 1980 Pritzker Prize, the highest award in architecture.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Mexican literature has its antecedents in the literature of the indigenous settlements of Mesoamerica.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Poetry had a rich cultural tradition in pre-Columbian Mexico, being divided into two broad categories—secular and religious.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Aztec poetry was sung, chanted, or spoken, often to the accompaniment of a drum or a harp.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] While Tenochtitlan was the political capital, Texcoco was the cultural center; the Texcocan language was considered the most melodious and refined.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] The best well-known pre-Columbian poet is Nezahualcoyotl.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] There are historical chronicles of the conquest of the Aztec Empire by participants, and, later, by historians.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Bernal Díaz del Castillo's *True History of the Conquest of the New Spain* is still widely read today.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Spanish-born poet Bernardo de Balbuena extolled the virtues of Mexico in *Grandeza mexicana* (Mexican Grandeur) (1604).
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Baroque literature flourished in the 17th century; the most notable writers of this period were Juan Ruiz de Alarcón and Juana Inés de la Cruz.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Sor Juana was famous in her own time, called the "Ten Muse".
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Nineteenth-century liberal of Nahua origin Ignacio Manuel Altamirano is an important writer of the era, along with Vicente Riva Palacio, the grandson of Mexican hero of independence Vicente Guerrero, who authored a series of historical novels as well as poetry.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] The late colonial-era novel by José Joaquín Fernández de Lizardi, *The Mangy Parrot* ("El Periquillo Sarniento"), is said to be the first Latin American novel.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] In the modern era, the novel of the Mexican Revolution by Mariano Azuela (*Los de abajo*, translated to English as *The Underdogs*) is noteworthy.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Poet and Nobel Laureate Octavio Paz, novelist Carlos Fuentes, Alfonso Reyes, Renato Leduc, essayist Carlos Monsiváis, journalist and public intellectual Elena Poniatowska, Juan Rulfo (*Pedro Páramo*), Martín Luis Guzmán, and Nellie Campobello (*Cartucho*) are other important Mexican writers.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Mexican films from the *Golden Age* in the 1940s and 1950s are the greatest examples of Latin American cinema, with a huge industry comparable to the Hollywood of those years.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Mexican films were exported and exhibited in all of Latin America and Europe.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] *María Candelaria* (1943) by Emilio Fernández, was one of the first films awarded a Palme d'Or at the Cannes Film Festival in 1946, the first time the event was held after World War II.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] The famous Spanish-born director Luis Buñuel realized in Mexico between 1947 and 1965 some of his masterpieces like *Los Olvidados* (1949) and *Viridiana* (1961).
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Famous actors and actresses from this period include María Félix, Pedro Infante, Dolores del Río, Jorge Negrete and the comedian Cantinflas.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] More recently, films such as *Como agua para chocolate* (1992), *Sex, Shame, and Tears* (1999), *Y tu mamá también* (2001), and *The Crime of Father Amaro* (2002) have been successful in creating universal stories about contemporary subjects, and were internationally recognized.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Mexico has a long tradition of music from the prehispanic era to the present.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Much of the music from the colonial era was composed for religious purposes.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] The most well-known Mexican composer of the twentieth century is Carlos Chávez (1899–1978), who composed six symphonies with indigenous themes, and rejuvenated Mexican music, founding the Orquesta Sinfónica Nacional.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Traditional Mexican music includes mariachi, banda, norteño, ranchera, and corridos.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Corridos were particularly popular during the Mexican Revolution (1910–20) and in the present era include narcocorridos.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] The embrace of rock and roll by young Mexicans in the 1960s and 1970s brought Mexico into the transnational, counterculture movement of the era.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] In Mexico, the native rock culture merged into the larger countercultural and political movement of the late 1960s, culminating in the 1968 protests and redirected into counterculture rebellion, *La Onda* (the wave).
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] On an everyday basis most Mexicans listen to contemporary music such as pop, rock, and others in both English and Spanish.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Folk dance of Mexico along with its music is both deeply regional and traditional.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Founded in 1952, the Ballet Folklórico de México performs music and dance of the prehispanic period through the Mexican Revolution in regional attire in the Palacio de Bellas Artes.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Some example of international success from Mexico Los Lobos, Maná, and Carlos Santana where is it in Rock and Roll Hall of Fame.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Bilingual government radio stations broadcasting in Spanish and indigenous languages were a tool for indigenous education (1958–65) and since 1979 the Instituto Nacional Indigenista has established a national network of bilingual radio stations.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] There was a major reform of the telecommunications industry in 2013, with the creation of new broadcast television channels.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] There had been a longstanding limitation on the number of networks, with Televisa, with a virtual monopoly; TV Azteca, and Imagen Television.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] New technology has allowed the entry of foreign satellite and cable companies.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Mexico became the first Latin American country to transition from analog to all digital transmissions.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] The origin of the current Mexican cuisine was established during the Spanish colonial era, a mixture of the foods of Spain with native indigenous ingredients.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Foods indigenous to Mexico include corn, pepper vegetables, calabazas, avocados, sweet potato, turkey, many beans, and other fruits and spices.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Similarly, some cooking techniques used today are inherited from pre-Columbian peoples, such as the nixtamalization of corn, the cooking of food in ovens at ground level, grinding in molcajete and metate.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] With the Spaniards came the pork, beef and chicken meats; peppercorn, sugar, milk and all its derivatives, wheat and rice, citrus fruits and another constellation of ingredients that are part of the daily diet of Mexicans.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] From this meeting of two millennia old culinary traditions, were born pozole, mole sauce, barbacoa and tamale in its current forms, chocolate, a large range of breads, tacos, and the broad repertoire of Mexican street foods.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Beverages such as atole, champurrado, milk chocolate and aguas frescas were born; desserts such as acitrón and the full range of crystallized sweets, rompope, cajeta, jericaya and the wide repertoire of delights created in the convents of nuns in all parts of the country.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] In 2005, Mexico presented the candidature of its gastronomy for World Heritage Site of UNESCO, the first time a country had presented its gastronomic tradition for this purpose.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] The result was negative, because the committee did not place the proper emphasis on the importance of corn in Mexican cuisine.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] In November 2010, Mexican gastronomy was recognized as Intangible cultural heritage by UNESCO.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] In April 2019, Daniela Soto-Innes was named the best female chef in the world by *The World's Best 50 Restaurants* and Elena Reygadas in 2023.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Organized sport in Mexico largely dates from the late nineteenth century, with only bullfighting having a long history dating to the early colonial era.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Once the political turmoil of the early republic was replaced by the stability of the Porfiriato did organized sport become public diversions, with structured and ordered play governed by rules and authorities.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Baseball was introduced from the United States and also via Cuba in the 1880s and organized teams were created.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] After the Mexican Revolution, the government sponsored sports to counter the international image of political turmoil and violence.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Mexico's most popular sport is association football.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] The bid to host the 1968 Summer Olympics was to burnish Mexico's stature internationally.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] The government spent abundantly on sporting facilities and other infrastructure to make the games a success, but those expenditures helped fuel public discontent with the government's lack of spending on social programs.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Mexico City hosted the XIX Olympic Games in 1968, making it the first Latin American city to do so.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Mexico hosted the 1970 FIFA World Cup and the 1986 FIFA World Cup and is co-hosting, along with Canada and the United States, the 2026 FIFA World Cup.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] With its past hosting of the 1970 and 1986 tournaments, Mexico has become the first country to host or co-host the men's World Cup three times.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Mexico is an international power in professional boxing.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Fourteen Olympic boxing medals have been won by Mexico.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] The Mexican professional baseball league is named the Liga Mexicana de Beisbol.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] While usually not as strong as the United States, the Caribbean countries and Japan, Mexico has nonetheless achieved several international baseball titles.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] *Lucha Libre* (freestyle professional wrestling) is also major crowd draw with national promotions such as CMLL, AAA and others.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Bullfighting is a popular sport in the country, and almost all large cities have bullrings.
[src:mexico/mexico-p03] Plaza México in Mexico City, which seats 45,000 people, is the largest bullring in the world.
[src:mexico/mx] After the three phases, .mx registrations were opened to the public.
[src:mexico/mx] Currently second level domains can be registered directly under .mx.
[src:mexico/mx] On 30 April 2009, second level domain registrations were 0.06% of the total.
[src:mexico/mx] A month later the value was up to 4.9% On 30 April 2010, second level registrations were 21.4% of the total.
